[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Series"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Learn Your Chess Classics book series is aimed at a wide range of players, from post-beginners in search of strategic footings to experts or even masters who want the most efficient plan to mastery in a specific pawn structure.  Each chapter narrates the main characters of the chess plot, the key squares in the battle and how to exploit them, typical pawn breaks, maneuvring of pieces, trades.  In short, each book in this series is a fully-fledged strategic manual on how to understand and play well the pawn formation studied.   Once the magistral part of the book ends, the reader can test his grasp of the material and go beyond it through tests that feature more than a hundred positions, all based on master or grandmaster practice.  In general, every example in those books is selected with the intention to further the student's questioning of our principles. Indeed, 'trust, but check' is an important mantra for any person aiming to improve his or her mastery of a subject.  LYCC has the ambition of becoming the reference of strategic exercise books, an area that, excepting Jacob Aagaard and Mark Dvoretsky's oeuvre, has not always given us the highest satisfaction. One might argue that those books are still too hard for the average player.  The book in your hands is the second in the LYCC series. It is our hope and expectation that a further five books shall be published by the end of 2019. Now to the author. Enjoy the journey!  Team LLR }
*


[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Author's Preface"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The book you have before you was long in the making. Indeed, I collected, in a manner very similar to Lazslo Polgar in his Middlegames and Endgames books, the full instructive content of games played in the Stonewall structure.  Those include all typical maneuvres, ideas, structural alterations and tactics that can be used in the Stonewall. Now, this is not only an opening book : I do not care about move orders from the start of the game or the latest wrinkle of theory. At least not in this issue.  Now, this does not mean that the Stonewall structure is limited to Dutch players. In fact, many of the examples taken here come from either the Queen's Indian or the Queen's Gambit Declined, where f5 was played at a later date. It is also possible to sail through the Slav, again via a timely f5, mostly when White is already committed to not putting his light-squared bishop on g2.  Back to the basics. If you had absolutely no idea about what this structure consisted in, the book cover must have alerted your senses by this point. Black is erecting a triangle d5-e6-f5 against White's centre represented by the d4-c4 duo. The battles you will see in this book will show you how the whole board can be a theatre of action in this deceptively dynamic structure.  To illustrate this, we'll first study captures on the system's two holes in the centre, namely e5 and e4, followed by other structural decisions, then piece play will be discussed. I'll show you some typical endgames for this structure before going into a hundred-plus exercises test.  This book can be used for at least two purposes:   
 the improving student can derive good and bad patterns of play in the Stonewall and improve his judgement of those positions. He can even build a repertoire based on those observations, in case he is too impatient to wait for the next installment of this series.   
The second use is related to trainers: the diagrams and exercises offered here allow for several hours of pinpointed questioning of a student with decent variety. It is my opinion that each chapter can fully serve a two to three hours intensive course to a level as high as 2200. In fact, I did use this content for that exact purpose with students of that level.  But enough talk! Please enjoy this book and if you have any questions or remarks pertaining to your experience of it, you can email me at leopsleruyet@gmail.com.   Leopold Le Ruyet, Guangzhou, China, May 2020 }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Burn, Amos vs. Chigorin, Mikhail Ivanovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/ppbn2pp/2p1pn2/2PpNp2/3P1B2/2N1P1P1/PP3PBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ At the start of this chapter, ask yourself who is better and, when two options arise, how White should capture on e5. This is the most common scenario : after all, the e5 square is supposed to be the Stonewall's Achilles' heel. So whether Black should or shouldn't capture an invading piece  (almost always a knight)  depends on two questions :   1-Is the trade beneficial ?   2-Is the change in the pawn structure favourable ? }
1... Nxe5 2. Bxe5 Bxe5 3. dxe5 Nd7 4. Qd4
{ The trade of knights was already not so bad for Black, but the change in the pawn structure is the main point. Put the b7 pawn on b5 and White would be better, but here... }
4... b6 5. Na4
{ It is important to understand that the opening of the a-file after   15.cxb6  15...axb6  Is in Black's favour. He also gains a strong and mobile pawns on b6 and c6, while e5 is still very weak }
5... Ba6
{ The key here is that c5 is not stable enough for White to dictate the game. You guessed it, d4 was supposed to be its defender! }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Kan, Ilia Abramovich vs. Konstantinopolsky, Alexander Markovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qrk1/pp1n2pp/2p1pb2/2PpN3/3PpB2/6P1/PPQ1PPBP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ So we saw how in this structure c4 may become weak once the d4 pawn leaves. But sometimes Black strikes from the other side ! }
1... Nxe5 2. dxe5 g5 { Black's central pawns are a very potent force! } 3. Be3
{ 15.exf6  15...gxf4  16.gxf4  16...e5  17.fxe5  17...Qxe5  18.Qb3  18...Rxf6  19.Qg3+  19...Qxg3  20.hxg3  Would have equalized, since f3 will soon follow. Still, I would pick Black who looks more in place despite his lag in development }
3... Bxe5 4. Bxg5 Qg6 5. Be3 Bg7 6. Qb3 e5
{ Black has a wonderful pawn center which proves to be too much for White to handle. }
7. f3 exf3 8. exf3 Rf7
{ A strong lateral defence to get the whole Black army in order ! From then on, White us given no quarters on the kingside. }
9. Qa3 Be6 10. Rf2 a6 11. Qa4 Raf8 12. Bc1 d4
{ Black's central pawns are a very potent force ! } 13. Rdf1 Bd5 14. b4 h5 15.
Qd1 h4 16. g4 Bc4 17. Re1 { Draw? } 17... Bd5 18. Ref1 Bc4 19. Re1 e4
{ Go jump in a lake, says Black, finishing the game with a flourish ! } 20.
Rxe4 Qxe4 21. fxe4 Rxf2 22. e5 Bxe5 23. Qe1 h3 24. Qxf2 Bxh2+ 25. Kxh2 Rxf2 26.
Kxh3 d3
{ An amazing attack by one of the strongest Soviet player of the WWII Era. } *


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Klasups, Karlis vs. Tal, Mihail"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1n2pp/2p1p3/2PpN3/3PpPQ1/2N1P3/PP3P1P/R3K2R b KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ It sometimes happens that White has controlled e5 with two pawns. The aforementioned plan still applies. }
1... Nxe5 2. fxe5 b6 3. Rg1 { One move threats are the best White can do :  . }
3... Qe7 { Defending g7. } 4. Na4 Ba6
{ Not being afraid of the capture on b6 as White would lose the b2 pawn. This is a superior position for Black. Compare the bishop and the knight. Enough said. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Beliavsky, Alexander G vs. Jussupow, Artur"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5rrk/pp2q1pp/2p5/3pnp1b/1P1P1P2/P1N1PPR1/1Q5P/6RK w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here on the other hand we have a case of a very poor trade on e5. What are the differences:   1  No Black pawn on e4   2  Nothing on c5   3  No Black pawn on e6. Oh, and   4  Black got nothing in return for the protected passed pawn on e5 and the crucial d4 square, for which he has no more light piece to defend. Keep that list in mind for later examples. }
1. dxe5
{ Black can't fight the protected passed pawn, his rooks are useless. His best bet is to play on the queenside but the d5 pawn is too weak to allow for the c-pawn to move away.   25.fxe5  f4  26.Rh3  g6  White's centre is too unstable. The difference is that the d4 lever would not bring any new weaknesses in White's camp But f4 sure does on f3, which happens to be on a light square. }
1... h6 2. Ne2 b6
{ Even with the move Black would still suffer after c5, but here it's even worse, as the knight lands even further into his position. }
3. Nd4 c5 { This also weakens d6. } 4. Nb5 Kh7 5. Nd6
{ And here it is a good moment to stop the trainable variation as White has vastly superior position. The remainder of the game is provided for completeness sake with only brief comments. }
5... g5
{ Desperate for counterplay, Yusupov now charges but he is rebuffed and taken out by the Ukrainian Cow-Boy. }
6. Qc2 Qe6 7. Rh3 Qg6 8. fxg5 hxg5 9. e6 Kh6 10. Nf7+ Rxf7 11. exf7 Qxf7 12.
bxc5 bxc5 13. Qxc5 Rg6 14. Qd4 Rg8 15. Rc1 Qe6 16. Rg3 g4 17. Qf4+ *


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Beliavsky, Alexander G vs. Van der Wiel, John"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp4pp/2p1pn2/3pnp2/2PP1P2/4P3/PP3PBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Remember that list? Remember the d4 square? You better have, since again Black is powerless in controlling it. Most impressive here is how all the waves still crash on the Ukrainian Cow-Boy's boots without so much as a drop reaching his toes. }
1. dxe5 Nd7
{ 11...Ne4  Might look more active, but the knight doesn't really threaten anything and actually gets into problems. After  12.b4  the c5 square is under White's control and f3 is a huge threat. Black has to play  12...Qb6  Attacking b4 and e3 and preventing f3  13.a3  Now threatening c5 followed by f3  13...dxc4  Giving up his beautiful Stonewall center  14.Bxe4  14...fxe4  15.Nd2  And White's knight is heading toward d6, attacking two weak pawns on the way and much superior to the poor bishop on c8 }
2. Nd2 Qe7 3. Rc1 Rd8 4. Qc2 Nf8 5. Nb3 Ng6 6. cxd5
{ Here we go. Black has two horrible choices: let White invade through the c-file or... }
6... exd5 7. Nd4
{ Give a protected passed pawn that our gunslinger knows how to use as we saw in the previous bit. }
7... Nh4 8. Bh3 g5
{ Desperation. Underdeveloped, with no target, the attack is sure to rebound on its maker. He who lived by the toothpick shall die by the tommy gun. }
9. Kh1 { White now calmly steps away... } 9... g4 10. Rg1 h5 11. Bf1 Rf8 12. f3
Rf7 13. Qf2 Ng6 14. Bd3 Kg7 15. b4
{ White knows he won on the kingside and centre, so he thinks 'why not make it the queenside too ?' }
15... a5 16. Qc2 Nh4 17. b5 cxb5 18. Qf2 Kf8 19. Bxb5 Nxf3 20. Nxf3 gxf3 21.
Qxf3 Be6 22. Rg6 d4 23. Rcg1 Qc5 24. Rxe6 Qxb5 25. Qg2
{ The a8 rook has still yet to move, as the horrendous bishop on c8 prevented its action. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Somacarana vs. Cochrane, John"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp4pp/2p1pn2/3pnp2/2PP1P1P/4P3/PP1NB1P1/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The next bit, as usual, concerns a situation where Black has not only traded one but two light pieces. You might want to look at it again when browsing the Taking on e4 Chapter. It also seems to be one of the first cases of a Stonewall gone so wrong. }
1. dxe5 Ne4 2. Nxe4 fxe4 3. g4
{ A rare occurrence : White attacks on the kingside, thanks to the closed centre. and Black's slumbering army. }
3... b6 4. g5 Bb7 5. h5 c5 6. h6
{ Picturesque, though not best. White puts all his pawns on dark squares so as to help his bishop and restrict Black's, not to mention that now one pawn falling anywhere will bring about all his brothers' doom. I only include the rest for the last move, since White could have conducted the fight better. White could have employed a similar plan as in the game, without moving the h-pawn too early.   16.cxd5  exd5  17.Qb3  Kh8  18.O-O-O  With a great game. The text move is more understandable from a human perspective, though. }
6... g6 7. Bg4 Re8 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Qb3
{ Creating an annoying pin along the c4-g8 diagonal and also trying to get something going along the d-file. }
9... a5
{ 19...c4  Is never a good idea, as it restricts the light-squared bishop even further }
10. Rd1 a4 11. Qb5 Re7 12. Rh2 Ra5 13. Qc4
{ Black will lose his e4 pawn or suffer the queen's arrival on the long diagonal. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Dimitrov, Dejan vs. Cheparinov, Ivan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5rk1/1b5r/2p2q2/pp1pbppB/3P1P2/4P1P1/PPRQ2K1/7R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. fxe5
{ White doesn't always capture with his d-pawn. He will here target the f-file and more broadly the Black king. But the immediate point is that he has to be able to play g4 to save his h5 bishop, concretely there shouldn't be anything on f4 !   34.dxe5  Qh8  35.g4  fxg4  36.Qd3  gxf4  37.exf4  Rxf4  38.Qg6+  Qg7  39.Qe6+  Kh8  40.Bg6  Rxh1  41.Kxh1  g3  42.Qh3+  Kg8  43.Qe6+  Kh8  is only a draw. }
1... Qh8 2. g4
{ 35...f4  Is even worse. After  36.exf4  Rxf4   36...gxf4  37.Qd3  f3+  38.Kf1  is no better  37.Qd3  White is once again significantly better. He is basically playing with an extra piece due to the sterile bishop on b7. }
2... fxg4 3. Qd3
{ Nothing to take on f4 this time ! The bishop on h5 is taboo because of the check on g6. White is significantly better. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar vs. Pelletier, Yannick"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn3rk1/3nq1pp/b1pbp3/p2pNp2/N1PP4/4Q1P1/PB2PPBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ I might have given the impression that as long as White is well prepared, taking on e5 is plane wrong. Let's start correcting this view with a move that 'must be bad', leaving White's dark squared bishop encumbered, with a concrete idea to justify it. } 
1... Bxe5 2. dxe5 Qb4
{ Letting the queen go to b4 through this trade happens more often than you'd think. Now c4 falls and with it all trace of White's construction. He's now close to lost. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Rossetto, Hector vs. Stahlberg, Gideon"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/1bpn2pp/1p1bp3/p2pNp2/2PPn3/PP1BP3/1B1NQPPP/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Now let's show a case where despite trading two light pieces, Black gets the upper hand through trading on e5. }
1... Bxe5 2. dxe5 Nxd2 3. Qxd2 Nc5
{ The potential opening of the long light diagonal and the c5 square are the deciding factors behind the trade on e5. Black is much better, since now White has let him either take b3 or trade the knight so that the opposite-colored bishop middlegame obviously favors the second player. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Nguyen, Duc Hoa vs. Dao, Thien Hai"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1q1rk1/1bp3pp/pp1b4/3pNp2/3Pn3/1P1BP3/PB1NQPPP/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Still, sometimes even with 3 light pieces on the board trading on e5 doesn't work out for Black. The passed pawn on e5 and Black's inability to create anything tangible on either wing means he's strategically lost. }
1... Bxe5 2. dxe5
{ Despite the huge difference of level, Black will be killed by White's bishops once the kingside opens up. Notice how badly developed Black is. To be honest, I can't explain why such a strong player would do this if not temporary insanity. }
2... Nc5 3. Bb1 Nbd7 4. b4 { Kicking the knight from an active square. } 4...
Ne6
{ Black maybe hoped that this blockading knight on e6 justifies his previous decision? Or he simply underestimated his opponent? }
5. f4 Qe7
{ When your best moves are one-move-threats, you know there is something wrong with your position. }
6. a3 c5 7. g4 { Just as in the Somarcana game. } 7... g6 8. h3
{ 20.gxf5  gxf5  21.Rf3  was even better. } 8... cxb4 9. axb4 Qxb4
{ Black is even a pawn up now but where it matters, on the kingside, he has nothing to stop the White army and the five moves it would take to promote seem like an awfully long time... White does not even need to be precise to finish the job. }
10. Bc3 Qe7 11. Kh2 Rac8 12. gxf5 gxf5 13. Nf3 Ndc5 14. Bb4 Kh8 15. Nd4 Ng7 16.
Rg1 Rc7 17. Rg5 Bc8 18. Rcg1 Rf7 19. Qg2 h6 20. Rg6 Qh4 21. Bxc5 bxc5 22. e6 *


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Caruana, Fabiano vs. Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1b2q1pp/nppbpn2/p2pNp2/2PP4/1P2P1P1/PB3PBP/1NRQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The computer hates the next decision by the world champion...and he's wrong ! }
1... Bxe5 2. dxe5 Ne4 3. Qe2 a4
{ Now the computer want to try some combination of f3 and Ba3 but can't get anywhere after that, so like a pigeon in the proverbial debate it claims victory by...well, you probably know the saying. }
4. Nc3
{ 16.Ba3  c5  17.f3   17.bxa4  Is a typical computer pawn grab that looks very wrong to a human eye because it ruins White's queenside pawn structure and provides Black with a clear target on a4.. and a2.  17...Ng5  18.Nc3  axb3  19.axb3  Rfd8  And Black has a perfectly reasonable position. He will eventually jump with the knight on b4 amd White's two bishop advantage is not felt since the position is fairly closed. }
4... axb3 5. axb3 Qb4
{ This is often a point of trading the d6 bishop so that it doesn't get in the way of the queen to b4. Pelletier anyone ? }
6. Nxe4 fxe4
{ With a double-edged position due to White's vulnerable queenside. Carlsen took with the d-pawn in the game, which is also fine. More on taking on e4 in a later chapter. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Dreev, Alexey vs. Radjabov, Teimour"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b2rk1/p2nq1pp/1r1bp3/1p1pNp2/1P1P4/2QN2P1/P3PPBP/1R3RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Nxe5
{ I think Radjabov was worried about the second White knight landing on c5 but now a rook gets there as the dark-squared bishop will stay on the bile-inducing b8 and the White queen patrols on the whole board through the newly-given d4 square.   18...Rb7  and Rc7 would have fought against White's domination of the c-file. }
2. dxe5 Bb8
{ A pretty sad retreat. The bishop will be restricted here forever. The problem is that after   19...Bc7  20.Rbc1  The bishop has to go to b8 all the same because  20...Bd8   20...Rb7  Is too ugly  21.Qxc8  He loses the other bishop }
3. Rfc1 Bb7 4. Qd4 Rc8 5. Rxc8+ Bxc8 6. Rc1 Bd7 7. Rc5
{ White has perfect domination on the dark squares. } 7... Kf8 8. h4
{ It may seem difficult for White to pierce through Black's armor but he has several angles to try out, from the c-file to the kingside levers, as well as a nice trick, missed by Dreev in the game. }
8... Rb7 9. Qc3 Qd8 10. Bxd5 { Said trick ! } 10... exd5 11. Rxd5
{ The point of White's combination. The pin is devastating and both Nc5 and e6 are threatend. }
11... Qb6 12. Nc5 Ke8 13. Qb3 Ke7 14. Nxd7 Rxd7 15. Rxd7+ Kxd7 16. Qf7+ Kd8 17.
Qg8+ Ke7 18. Qxg7+ Ke6 19. Qf6+ Kd5 20. Qxf5 Bxe5 21. Qxh7
{ At the end of this very long line, White gets all the pawns in the world, which is good as Russia faced this very World on that day ! }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Faizrakhmanov, Ramil vs. Volkov, Sergey"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/pb1nq1pp/1p1bp3/3pNp2/3Pn3/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/1QR2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Nxe5 2. dxe5 Bc5
{ An uncommon sight : the dark squared bishop lands on c5. Again food for thought when the trade of c-pawns operates on d5. }
3. Qd3 f4
{ Black has a now a raging initiative on the kingside thanks to the Bc5. } *


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Alatortsev, Vladimir vs. Konstantinopolsky, Alexander Markovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6rk/1p2qnpp/p1p1br2/3pNp2/3P1P1P/1P2P1P1/P2Q2B1/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Nxe5
{ Much like Dao, Konstantinopolsky hopes he will be able to generate play on the queenside through c5. He's never even close to being in time and I believe he may have been in a must-win situation to try such folly.   32...Nd6  and White is not going anywhere. }
2. dxe5 Rff8 3. b4 { Starting to control the dark-squares. } 3... Rc8 4. Qd4
{ We know this theme by now. The d4 square is used as an outpost for the White Queen, from which she reigns on the centre and supervises pawn breaks on the queenside. The key is that with a pawn on a6 instead of a7, Black can never even dream of going b6-c5 in time. }
4... Qc7 5. Rf2 a5 6. a3 axb4 7. axb4 Ra8 8. b5 Qd7 9. bxc6 bxc6 10. Qc5 Rgc8
11. Rfc2 h6 12. Kf2 Kh7 13. Bf3 Qd8 14. Be2 Ra5 15. Qb4 Bd7 16. Bd3 c5 17. Rxc5
Raxc5 18. Rxc5 Qf8 19. Qb7 *


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Vaganian, Rafael A vs. Bronstein, David Ionovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pp4pp/4pb2/2ppN3/2PPp3/4BPP1/PP2P1BP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

Bxe5
{ No hesitation as White's dark squared bishop will soon be of no value, as it now locked in by e3. Still all is not so simple. }
2. dxe5 d4 3. Bc1 Nc6
{ 13...e3  14.b4 !  cxb4  15.a3  And White is much better. } 4. f4
{ 14.fxe4  Rxf1+  15.Qxf1  b6  Stockfish claims equality. I was at first taken aback but Black only can go forward by opening the position, where the abomination on g2 may become human again. }
4... e3 5. b3
{ 15.Bxc6  Might be worthy of consideration, trying to ruin Black's pawn structure and play against the c5 pawn, but it is not natural for a human to give up his good bishop so easily. }
5... Qb6
{ Defending the knight and preparing a5-a4 ideas. The immediate   15...a5  Is now definitely met with  16.Bxc6  bxc6  17.Ba3  Qb6  18.Rb1  And it is hard for Black to make progress in this position }
6. Be4 a5 { Threatening a4. } 7. Rb1 { Meeting that threat. } 7... Qc7
{ The queen has done her duty on b6. } 8. a3 Rd8 9. Qe1 Bd7 10. g4 g5
{ Undermining the e5 pawn as well as preventing Qh4. White is two pieces down on the kingside and might as well resign. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Van Wely, Loek vs. Ulybin, Mikhail"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r1rk1/1b2q1pp/1p1bp3/pN1pN3/2PPp3/1P4P1/4Q1BP/2BR2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Bxe5
{ This time Black wants to trade rooks, as he should since he has two to White's one : in general when playing with a rook and pawns against two pieces this strategy is the right one since the rook is the enemy pawns worst enemy and its passed troopers best friend. }
2. dxe5 dxc4 3. Ba3 Rxd1+ 4. Qxd1 Rd8
{ Thanks to this intermediate move, Black manages to gain control of the d-file and transition into a winning endgame. }
5. Qf1 { 25.Bxe7  Rxd1+  Is, of course, losing for White } 5... Qd7
{ The queen is going for the key d3-square. } 6. bxc4 Qd3
{ Black is going to invade with his rook on both sides of the board and once queens are traded, there won't be anyone preventing it from helping the a-pawn to victory, since the bishop on a3 won't be stable after Bc6 attacks its defender, the knight. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi vs. Bosiocic, Marin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1b1r1rk1/pb2q1p1/4p3/2p1Np1p/2N1nPn1/1P2P1P1/PB2Q1BP/2RR2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Bxe5 { The b8 bishop has no future, contrary to the e5-c4 tandem. } 2.
Nxe5 { 22.Bxe5  Ba6 ! } 2... Nxe5
{ But this trade is wrong !   22...Rxd1+  23.Rxd1  Rd8  Black takes over the d-file and the White bishops don't allow for any edge. }
3. Bxe5 h4 4. g4 h3 5. Bxe4
{ Exchanges such as this one show a class of a player. White gives up his bishop for the strong knight because in the resulting opposite coloured bishop middlegame correctly judges he will have be able to control the game and collect weak pawns on the queenside. He might also grab the initiative if Black is not careful, while it is difficult for Black to create any attacking chances. 2700 level understanding, ladies and gentleman. }
5... Bxe4 6. g5
{ With the kingside closed up, it's time to face the tax collector on the other side. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Fridman, Daniel vs. Nikolic, Predrag"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rr2k1/1b1nq1pp/np1bp3/p1ppNpP1/2PP1P2/1P1NP3/PB4BP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Bxe5 { Without the e5 knight, White is suffering in the centre. } 2. fxe5
{ 20.Nxe5  Nxe5  21.dxe5  dxc4  And Black loses material due to the discovered attack on the queen   20.dxe5  Nf8  And one knight is coming to g6, the other to b4 }
2... Nf8
{ Making sure everything is neatly covered on d5 : we don't want another protected passed pawn on e5 in this chapter ! }
3. h4 Ng6 4. h5 Nh4
{ The point of it all : g5 falls, the bishop on b7 will roar once g2 is but a souvenir of White's begone dreams. }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Melkumyan, Hrant vs. Adhiban, Baskaran"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pb2q1pp/1p1bp3/2ppNp2/2PPn3/1P2P1P1/PB2QPBP/R2R2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ An uncommon theme has long-term ramifications. } 1... Bxe5 2. dxe5 dxc4
{ 18.Qxc4  Ng5  19.Qe2  Rad8  is still fine for Black, but nowhere as good as what happens in the game. }
3. bxc4 Rfd8 4. h4
{ Did White think he would trap the knight? Most likely he wanted to prevent it from landing on f3 later on.  Trying to exchange all rooks was probably better. After   19.Rxd8  Rxd8  20.Rd1  Rxd1+  21.Qxd1  Bc6  Black is still in the driver's seat due to the better pawn structure, but White has definite drawing chances }
4... Bc6
{ The trade on c4 was done in order to go to a4! Now the d-file is in Black's hands. Look at that pantomime on b2. Just as in previous note, White could now try   20.Rxd8  Rxd8  21.Rd1  But now Black plays  21...Ba4  22.Rxd8+  Qxd8  and obtains a better version of the previously examined variation due to his control of the d-file }
*


[White "Taking on e5"]
[Black "Bai, Jinshi vs. Wei, Yi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb2rk1/pp4pp/3bp3/2p1Np2/2PPp3/2P1B1P1/P3PPBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ And finally, a queenless middlegame that will soon mimick a Nimzo-Indian's player dreams. }
1... Bxe5 2. dxe5 b6
{ Reinforcing the weak pawn before continuing development. White can't exploit Black's temporarily slumbering pieces on the queenside. }
3. f3 { Trying to undermine the center and open up his bishop... } 3... Bb7
{ ... but he will have none of that. } 4. fxe4 Bxe4
{ With the trade of light-squared bishops the c4 pawn has lost his last potential defender. Though the computer find ways to keep on playing here, for all intents and purposes it's over now. }
5. Bxe4 fxe4 6. Rxf8+ Kxf8 7. Rf1+ Ke8 8. Rd1 { 20.Rf4  Nc6  21.Rxe4  Rd8 }
8... Nc6 9. Bf4 Na5
{ The c4 pawn is condemned in the long term, as isolated doubled pawns often are, particularly the one in front, since no defence may derive from its file. }
10. h4 Nxc4 11. h5 Rd8 12. Rf1 h6 13. Kf2 Nb2 14. Rc1 Rd1 15. Kg2 Rxc1 16. Bxc1
Nc4 17. Bf4 a5 18. Kf2 a4 19. g4 b5 20. Ke1 b4 21. Kd1 b3 22. axb3 a3
{ A nice little tactic to end this crucial chapter. } *


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Fine, Reuben vs. Alekhine, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp4pp/2n1pb2/3p1p2/2PNn3/1P4P1/PBQNPPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's start with a straight-forward example. } 1. Nxe4 fxe4
{ 12...dxe4  13.Nxc6  bxc6  14.Rad1  Qe7  15.Bxf6  Rxf6  16.Rd2  When Black takes back with the d-pawn, the d-file is often the deciding factor. Here White is obviously in control of it, which explains his winning advantage. }
2. Rad1 Qb6 3. Nb5
{ The d5 pawn is targeted : if Black trades on c4, the e4 pawn will soon drop. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Makogonov, Vladimir Andreevich vs. Ragozin, Viacheslav"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r2r2k/q6p/P1p1bb2/2Np1p2/3PnP2/2B5/6RP/R1Q2B1K w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxe4
{ White already won on the queenside but he has to create a second front to claim victory. }
1... fxe4
{ 34...dxe4  35.d5 !  Is horrible for Black, as his king will not survive the weakening of the a1-h8 diagonal. }
2. f5
{ Capturing on e4 can open lines or leave available squares. Here White gained access to the kingside. }
2... Bc8
{ Taking the pawn with   35...Bxf5  is, of course, too dangerous, but White has to be precise.  36.Rf2!   36.Qf4  is inferior because it leaves the rook on a1 and bishop on d4 unprotected  36...Bxd4  37.Bxd4  Qxd4  and White can't capture on f5 because his rook on a1 is hanging  36...Qd7  37.Qf4  Only now when the black queen is not attacking d4 does White include his queen and wins one of the bishops }
3. Qh6
{ Black is better in the centre, for all the good that does him : he's busted on both wings and Makogonov annihilates Ragozin from here. }
3... Qe7 4. a7
{ Black is unable to handle the combined pressure on the kingside and the threats created by the a-pawn. }
4... Ra8 5. Bb4
{ Trying to deflect the queen from the defence of the f6 bishop. } 5... Qf7 6.
Be2 Bxd4 7. Bh5 Qxf5 8. Rag1
{ And White has a winning position because of the dual-threat of taking the rook on e8 and Bc5  (diverting the bishop from the defence of the g7 square)  . }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Drozdovskij, Yuri vs. Wang, Yue"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1q2rk1/p2nbbpp/2p1p3/2Pp1pN1/Q2Pn3/2N3P1/P2BPPBP/1R3RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ncxe4
{ The idea of this move is to open the diagonal and expose the e6 pawn. } 1...
fxe4 { 17...dxe4  18.f3 !  Once e4 is gone, the c6 pawn will die. } 2. Nxf7
{ A somewhat surprising capture, but it is important to eliminate the defender of the pawn on e6. This move also avoids the capture on g5, followed by e5, which would arise after   18.Bh3  Bxg5  19.Bxg5  and now maybe  19...e5  is playable, because after  20.dxe5  Nxc5  seems unclear. It is wiser to avoid all this. }
2... Rxf7 3. Bh3 Nf8 4. f3
{ After a trade on f3, White will easily target e6 with his rooks. } *


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Dubov, Daniil vs. Kozak, Adam"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1n2pp/2pbpq2/3p4/2PPnp2/1P3NP1/PB1NPPBP/R1QR2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a purely tactical example. Remember this idea with a Qc1-Bb2 battery. In fact White often trades the dark squared bishop this way. }
1. Nxe4 dxe4 2. Nd2 { 13.d5  Is probably also sufficient, but Nd2 is simpler. }
2... fxg3 3. Nxe4 gxf2+ 4. Kh1
{ Even though it may look scary at first glance, the white king is perfectly safe and tactics work in White's favour.   15.Kf1  Is bad, because Black has  15...Qh4  with ideas of ...Qxh2 and ...Qg1, with mate. }
4... Qe7 5. Nxd6 Qxd6 6. Ba3
{ White wins an exchange and obtains a winning position. } *


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar vs. Idani, Pouya"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pb1nq1pp/1p1b4/2ppNp2/3Pn3/1P1BP3/PBQN1PPP/2RR2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxe4
{ In this example, the exchange on e4 includes a very deep sacrificial idea, exploiting the potential pin on the d-file. You don't see the pin in the making? Let's see how it came to be. }
1... fxe4 2. Bxe4 dxe4 3. Nxd7 Qxd7
{ Now Black is just lost.   17...cxd4  18.Nxf8  d3  19.Qc4+  Kxf8  20.f4  White will attack through the f-file straight to the Black king.   17...Rf5 !  18.dxc5  bxc5  19.Qc4+  Kh8  20.Rxd6  Qxd6  21.Nxc5  Although White has two pawns for the exchange and active pieces, Black's potential on the open d and f files allow for approximate equality. }
4. dxc5 Bxh2+ { Forced, because   18...bxc5  runs into  19.Be5 } 5. Kxh2 Qc7+
6. Kg1 Rac8
{ 20...bxc5  Was probably the lesser evil, but White is still vastly superior after  21.Qc4+  Kh8  22.b4  Utilizing the pin on the c-file and obtaining what is probably a technically winning position }
7. Qc4+ Rf7 8. cxb6 Qxb6 9. Qa4
{ White is a pawn up with the initiative since Black is not in time to foment cruel designs upon the f2 pawn. This is a good place to end the trainable variation as the 'rest is the matter of technique', as the lazy annotators often like to say :  ! }
9... Rcf8 10. Rd7 Rxd7 11. Qxd7 Rf7 12. Qe8+ Rf8 13. Qa4 a6 14. Qc4+ Rf7 15.
Rd1 Qc7 16. Qe6 Qe7 17. Ba3 *


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Li, Chao B vs. Ulybin, Mikhail"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1nq1pp/2p1pb2/3pNp2/2PPnB2/2N3P1/PPQ1PPBP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxd7
{ It is always surprising to exchange a well-placed knight on e5 for the 'bad' knight on d7, but here White wants to follow it up with an exchange on e4. It was also possible to play   12.Nxe4  Immediately, but here White would have to count on rejoinder  12...Bxe5  13.dxe5  fxe4  when it is not possible to execute the same c5 idea as in the game. Still, this position also looks better for White, so we can conclude he was spoilt for choice in the initial position }
1... Bxd7 2. Nxe4 fxe4 { 13...dxe4  14.c5!  Is similar. } 3. c5
{ Another key idea once there is no knight to protect d6. } 3... e5
{ Desperation, but Black prefers active measures instead of going passive with   14...Qd8  15.Bd6  Be7  16.Bxe7  Qxe7  17.f3  And the position opens in White's favour. Still, it was a better alternative than the game continuation. }
4. dxe5 Bxe5 5. Bxe5 Qxe5 6. Bxe4
{ Black has very little if anything for the lost pawn. } *


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Verlinsky, Boris vs. Chistiakov, Alexander Nikolaevi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3q2k/p5pp/b1pb1r2/3pNp2/2nPnP2/1QN2BP1/P3P2P/1RB2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxe4
{ Black built his whole construction around the light squares but it simply fails here. }
1... fxe4 2. Qa4
{ The immediate   22.Nxe4  runs into a crazy line starting with  22....dxe4  23.Nxc4  Rb8  24.Nxd6  Rxb3  25.Nxe8  Rxb1  26.Nxf6  Bxe2!  and apparently this position is completely equal. }
2... Bc8
{ This move is bad, but Black's position was unenviable all the same.   22...c5  23.Qxe8+  Rxe8  24.Nxd5  Is good for White, but he has less clear advantage than after the text move.   22...Qc8  23.Nxe4 !  23...dxe4  24.Nxc4  Bb5  25.Nxd6  Rxd6  26.Qc2  Also work in White's favour. }
3. Nxd5
{ Avoiding all tricks. Black was hoping for   23.Qxc6  Qxc6  24.Nxc6  Bc5  25.dxc5  Rxc6  With some hopes of salvation }
3... Bxe5 4. dxe5 Rf7 5. Nc3 Be6 6. Nxe4
{ Two pawns down, passive heavy pieces, protected passed pawn on e5 : the devil called and wants his nightmares back. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Najdorf, Miguel vs. Guimard, Carlos Enrique"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/pp1bb1pp/1n2p3/3p1p2/3PP3/2PQ1PPN/P5BP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Now that we saw how White can exploit the trade on e4, let's have a look at what Black can do and how he should recapture. }
1... dxe4
{ Stronger than taking with the f-pawn. If   15...fxe4  16.fxe4  e5  Black's pawn on d5 is hanging. He has compensation in form of ...exd4 and ...Bf5 ideas after:  17.exd5  exd4  18.cxd4  Bf5  19.Qb3  But the situation is unclear, therefore taking with the d-pawn is to be preferred. }
2. fxe4 e5
{ White has overextended : either fe4 or f4 will follow : Black is just better. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Trifunovic, Petar vs. Milic, Borislav"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp1bb2p/2p1p3/2Pp1p1q/3PNPp1/3Q2P1/PP1BP1BP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxe4 2. Qc2 Qg6 { Creating space for the advance of the h-pawn. } 3. e3 h5
4. Ba5 { Trying to activate the bishop via the c7 square. } 4... Rfc8
{ Very precise! Black prevents the bishop from reaching c7. Next Black will go Rab8-b6, h4, Kf7 and Rh8 with opportunities on both sides. Note that the more natural   18...Rac8  was actually a bad mistake, because after  19.Qb3  there is no convenient way to defend the b-pawn, as  19...Rb8  runs into  20.Bc7 }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Inkiov, Ventzislav vs. Anceschi, Vittorio"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp2b2p/2p1p2q/3pPp2/2P1Np2/1P2P1P1/PB4BP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxe4
{ 16...fxe4  17.gxf4  Bd7  18.Kh1  White now has the option to play f5 and open up the a1-h8 diagonal. Besides Black has no claim to the open d file since it's still closed.   16...f3  would be a nice intermediate move, were it not for  17.Nf6+ }
2. exf4
{ 17.gxf4  Rd8  18.Qe2  Bd7  19.Kh1  Be8  Bh5 guarantees Black superiority. }
2... Rd8 3. Qe2 Bc5+ 4. Kh1 Bd7 { The same idea gives Black a solid edge. } 5.
Rad1 Be8
{ Developing naturally and harmoniously. All Black's pieces are now participating in the game. }
6. Rxd8 Rxd8 7. Rd1 Rxd1+ 8. Qxd1 Bf2
{ Black is completely dominating the position - both White's bishops are restricted and his king is also weaker  (despite the fact that Black's king has little pawns in front of him)  .  It has to be mentioned that   24.Qd8  doesn't achieve anything because of  24...Qh5  and the bishop on e8 has been defended and the threat of Bxg3 still remains. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Gavrikov, Viktor vs. Kortschnoj, Viktor Lvovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1q1rk1/pbp1b1pp/1p2p3/3p1p2/2PPN3/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxe4
{ Black can target the d4 pawn and keeps the e6 pawn secure. In fact, as for the capture on e5, taking back with the d pawn is most often the right choice.   10...fxe4  11.Bh3 ! }
2. f3 Bf6
{ Immediately applying pressure on the d4 pawn.  There is nothing wrong with starting with   11...Nc6  but the bishop move is a tad move forcing. }
3. Be3 Nc6 4. fxe4 Bxd4 5. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 6. Qxd4 Nxd4
{ The resulting exchanges can be definitely regarded as a success for Black. His knight is dominating on d4. Also, there is an immediate threat of ...Nc2. }
7. Rac1 fxe4 8. Nxe4 c5
{ Since all pieces on the board are active and the structure is symmetrical, the position is about equal. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Tregubov, Pavel V vs. Bauer, Christian"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/ppp3pp/4pb2/3p1p2/2PPN3/1P4P1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Sometimes even dxe4 is not enough for Black. Let's have a look at other strategies White can use. }
1... dxe4
{ 10...fxe4  11.Nc3  White will play e3 and f3, targeting the d5 pawn once the trade has been done on f3. }
2. Qd2 { Preparing to deal with the upcoming pressure on the d-pawn. } 2... c5
3. Rd1 Nc6
{ 12...cxd4  13.Bxd4  Bxd4  14.Qxd4  Qe7  15.Nc3  Nc6  16.Qd2  Rd8  may also be fine, although f3-g4 seems like a dangerous duo to contain. }
4. d5
{ This is actually a cold shower for Black. No pressure on d4 today, my friend. }
4... exd5 5. cxd5 Bxb2 6. Qxb2 Nd4 { 15...Qd6  16.Nd2  Ne5  17.f4 ! } 7. e3
{ The difference compared to the previous example. The knight gets chased from it's nice outpost. }
7... Nb5 8. a4 Nd6
{ The position favors White since he can easily trade the blockading knight through Na3-c4, and even prepare it with Bf1. Black's light-squared bishop is severely restricted with the pawn on d5 but also by his own pawn on f5. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Kacheishvili, Giorgi vs. Antal, Gergely"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb2rk1/pp2b3/2p1pnqp/3p1pp1/2PPP3/5PP1/PPQB1NBP/RN1R2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxe4
{ In this example, taking with the d-pawn is good - not because of the pressure on d4, but because it can be followed up with an immediate e5.   13...fxe4  Is not so good because the position arising after  14.fxe4  e5  15.cxd5  cxd5  16.dxe5  Ng4  17.Nxg4  Bxg4  is not so easy to evaluate. The engines claim White is slightly better after the exchange sacrifice  18.Nc3 }
2. fxe4 e5
{ 14...f4  15.gxf4  gxf4  16.Bxf4  c5  17.dxc5  e5  18.Be3  Bg4  19.Kh1 !  Bxd1  20.Qxd1  Nc6  With a very tense battle as well. }
3. dxe5
{ The other capture is even worse, but needs to be checked:   14.exf5  Bxf5  15.Qb3  and now Black has very strong  15...Nbd7  ignoring the threat to his b7 pawn because if he captures it, another Black piece joins the action:  16.Qxb7  Rab8  17.Qxc6  Rb6  18.Qc7  Rxb2  with tremendous compensation for just one pawn. }
3... Ng4 4. Nxg4 fxg4
{ The e5 pawn is not stable and Black is at least not worse. } *


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Bisguier, Arthur Bernard vs. Zaltsman, Vitaly F"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pbpnq2p/1p1bp3/3p1pp1/2PPN3/1P2PN2/PB3PPP/R2QRBK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxe4
{ 14...fxe4  15.Ne5  Bxe5  16.dxe5  Rf5  illustrates a point of taking with the f pawn ! }
2. Ne5 Nxe5 3. dxe5 Bb4
{ The dark square bishop has proliferated because the obstacles in the center have been removed. }
4. Re2 a5
{ Black controls both sides and will follow up with either a4 or f4. } *


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Salov, Valery vs. Naumkin, Igor"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/1p1bb1pp/2p1p3/p2p1p2/2PPP3/2PQ1PP1/P5BP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... fxe4 2. fxe4 dxc4 3. Qxc4
{ At first glance it seems White has a beautiful center, but Black has concrete ways of undermining it! }
3... b5
{ 17.Qb3  seems more logical at first, but after  17...a4  18.Qb2  e5  Black carries out his desired idea and undermines the center nevertheless }
4. Qd3 e5
{ Four changes in a row ! Despite its apparent solid static appearance, the Stonewall can be incredibly fluid. }
5. Be3
{ 18.d5  Also seems logical, but weakens the dark-squares too much. Black has sveral good ways of continuing. The most clear-cut seems to be  18...Qb6+  19.Be3  c5  and the d-pawn is not going anywhere in the near future, while Black's queenside pawn majority is extremely dangerous   18.dxe5  Grabbing the pawn is very greedy as it ruins White's pawn structure. Black has many good replies, but the simplest seems to be  18...Qc7  aiming to recapture the pawn immediately.  19.Bf4  Be6  and Black has a fantastic compensation for the pawn.    But not   19...g5  20.e6! }
5... Qc7
{ One rook on d8, one on b8 and c5 to take over the queenside : Black is just better. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Miljkovic, Miroslav D vs. Sedlak, Nikola"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/1p6/p1p2b2/P1PpNp1n/1P1PnPpp/2N1Q1P1/7P/2BRR1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxe4 dxe4 2. d5 cxd5 3. Qb3
{ Black is just dead through the d-file. Note that   33...Bxe5  is met with  34.Rxd5 }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Illescas Cordoba, Miguel vs. Polugaevsky, Lev"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qbrk1/pp1n2pp/2pbp3/3pNp2/2PPN3/1P4P1/PB2PPBP/R1Q2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxe4 2. f3
{ A reasonable try but Black should be spoilt for choice   13.c5  Bc7  14.Nxd7  Qxd7  15.f3  exf3  16.Rxf3  Bg6  Black is the one in possession of the levers : even if the position is about equal, I'd rather take him. }
2... Nxe5 3. dxe5 Bc5+
{ A familiar idea by now  (I hope :D)  : Once the d-pawn is gone, the weakening of the a7-g1 diagonal can be exploited. }
4. Kh1 exf3 5. exf3 Qe7
{ Not the most precise  (the queen didn't need to prevent Ba3)  . I can't see a plan for White and Black can improve his position on the kingside, though objectively the computer reminds me this is supposed to be equal. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Biebinger, Gerhard vs. Volkov, Sergey"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/4q1pp/nppbp3/p2p1p2/2PPn3/1P3NP1/PB1NPPBP/1QR2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxe4 { White should first secure the centre before he opens it ! } 1... dxe4
2. Ne5 c5
{ The position is about equal for Stockfish  (I'm arguing for Black still since he has more space but White does have f3 to trade the dangerous e4 pawn)  but White started with a favourable version  (several tempi up compared to the theoretical chapter)  , so all in all the trade in e4 was not a glorious affair. }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Gormally, Daniel vs. Shabalov, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp2q1pp/2p1p3/3pPp2/2PPN3/4P3/PP3PBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... fxe4
{ In this case the fight for the f-file rages on and White falls apart when he takes his eyes off the pitch, let alone the ball. White not having knights or a dark square bishop makes Black's endaveour perfectly playable. }
2. f3 exf3 3. Rxf3 Bd7
{ As usual the bishop wants to go Be8-g6-e4 or Be8-h5.   15...Rxf3  16.Qxf3  dxc4 !  this prevents c5 for good ! }
4. Rxf8+
{ It was probably better not to play in Black's hands by granting him control of the f-file, but after   16.c5!  Black can either continue with the bishop maneuver after exchanging rooks on f3 or play the undermining  16...b6  to open a second front on the queenside. In either case the position is about equal. }
4... Rxf8 5. Qe2 Qg5 6. b3
{ Now   18.c5  was mandatory, preventing the possibility mentioned in the comments to Black's next move }
6... Be8 { 18...dxc4  19.bxc4  c5  would have been stronger } 7. Qe1
{ An inexplicable mistake!   19.Rf1  Rxf1+  20.Kxf1  Bh5   20...Qf5+  21.Kg1  Bh5  is more precise but is still within the drawing margin.  21.Bf3  Bxf3  22.Qxf3  b5  would just be equal. }
7... Rf3 { Now Black is just winning. } 8. e4 dxe4 9. Qxe4 Rf4
{ And White resigned since he is unable to defend the d4 pawn after   22.Qd3   22.Qe3  Rf1+  loses on the spot  22...Bg6  22.Qe2   22.Qd2  once again runs into  22...Rf1+  22...Rxd4 }
*


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Wunnink, Michael vs. Reinderman, Dimitri"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/3nq1pp/bppbp3/p2p1p2/2PPn3/1PNNP1P1/PB2QPBP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxe4 { The punishment is different this time ! } 1... fxe4
{ 16...dxe4  is also possible } 2. Ne5 Bxe5 3. dxe5 b5
{ The point! Black undermines the queenside pawn structure and opens his slumbering bishop! }
4. cxd5 cxd5
{ Black has preferable prospects as White is deprived of any plans. } *


[White "Taking on e4"]
[Black "Schussler, Harry vs. Agdestein, Simen"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5rk1/pb2r3/np2q3/2pp1pp1/3Pn3/PPN1PNP1/1Q3PB1/2RR2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxe4 fxe4
{ What follows is an example of the rule already stated twice : when White is acting on the queenside, attack on the kingside ! }
2. Nxg5 Qh6 3. Nh3
{ The engine points out that   22.f4  is somewhat more resistant, but no human would ever play it }
3... Bc8 4. Nf4 Bg4
{ Not so much threatening the rook on d1 as much as taking the e2 square under control and creating mating threats involving the move Bf3. }
5. Kf1
{ Just to illustrate Black's idea, let's assume White makes some 'non-moves'   24.Qa2  Rh7  25.Qb2  now Black has a forced mate starting with  25...Qh2+  26.Kf1  Qh1+  very beautiful!  27.Bxh1  Rxh1+  and now note how important it is that the king can't escape via the e2 square. Also, the bishop is the one that has the pleasure of delivering the fatal blow:  28.Kg2  Bf3 }
5... Qh2
{ Of course, Black has no interest in capturing the rook  (for the moment)  . White will be savagely disemboweled from here, the attack plays itself as the knight can't seriously hope to stop the whole Black army. }
6. dxc5 Rh7 { Once again, the threat is Qh1+. } 7. Ke1 Rxf4
{ Not strictly neccessary, but fully correct and sufficient for the win. } 8.
gxf4 Qg1+ 9. Kd2 { 28.Bf1  Rh1  is also game over } 9... Qxf2+ 10. Kc3 Qxe3+
11. Kc2 Bxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Rh2
{ And as they say - the rest doesn't require additional commentary. } 13. Rd2
Nxc5
{ 32...Qxd2  33.Kxd2  Rxg2  was a faster way toward victory, but Black doesn't spoil it anyway }
14. Qc3 Qxf4 15. b4 Nd3 16. Qc8+ Kg7 17. Qd7+ Kf6 18. Qxd5 Rxg2 19. Qd4+ Ke7
20. Rxg2 Ne1+ 21. Kb3 Nxg2 22. Qg7+ Qf7+ 23. Qxf7+ Kxf7 24. Kc3 e3 25. Kd3 Ke6
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Tarrasch, Siegbert vs. Leonhardt, Paul Saladin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4rrk1/pppb2pp/1n2pq2/3pNp2/3Pn3/1PPNQ1P1/P3PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Not everything revolves around e4 and e5. To decipher precisely where one should use his lever, deliberately asking 'where to go now ?' is key. Most players charge without stopping to consider there are three areas to choose from. Here the centre is fixed, the kingside is under control so where should White play ? That's right, on the queenside ! No need to go for some crazy f3-e4 when Black on has a knight to his right. }
1. c4 Bc8 2. c5 Nd7 3. c6
{ Rarely will you see White get this opportunity : the theoretical part will make sure that as Black it can never happen. }
3... bxc6 4. Nxc6 { Now Black has weaknesses on the queenside. } 4... a6 5.
Rac1 g5 6. Nde5 Qg7 7. Bxe4 dxe4
{ 22...fxe4  23.Nxd7  Bxd7  24.Ne5  doesn't change much } 8. Nxd7
{ This and the previous move were great decisions to exchange minor pieces and remain with a dominant knight against a bad bishop. }
8... Bxd7 9. Ne5 Bc8 { Now that we've weakened Black's structure, time to... }
10. f4
{ ...secure the dark squares. At this point, Black should take en passant but would still be lost. This is a good moment to end the trainable variation as White is completely dominating and had no problems in converting his advantage. }
10... gxf4 11. Qxf4
{ Black bishops hates binds. Repeat that in your head with a thick Russian accent. That should do the trick. }
11... Bb7 12. e3 Bd5 13. Rc5 Re7 14. Rfc1 Ra8 15. Nc6 Rf7 16. Nb4 c6 17. Nxc6 *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Geller, Efim P vs. Szabo, Laszlo"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qrk1/p2n3p/2p1pb2/1p1p1pp1/1PPPn3/3N1NP1/P1Q1PPBP/1RB2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ There are also cases where you decide NOT TO act on one side. In general, having a NOT TO DO list can be pretty useful during your game, like a mental list of your position's allergies. }
1. c5
{ Now that the queenside is closed, White will be ousting the e4 knight. } 1...
a5 2. a3 axb4 3. axb4 g4 4. Nfe5 Nxe5 5. dxe5
{ Now f3, evicting the knight, will come at some point. Once again, White's control of dark squares yields him an advantage. }
5... Bd8 6. Bh6 Rf7 7. f3 { Here we go ! Black now only has bad pieces. } 7...
Bg5 8. Bxg5 Nxg5 9. fxg4
{ With no knight to safeguard the centre, it will naturally start collapsing through the kingside. }
9... Rfa7
{ 22....fxg4  23.Nf2  simply wins the g4 pawn because  23...h5  is impossible due to  24.Qg6+  and the knight on g5 drops because  24....Rg7  drops the queen after  25.Qxe8 }
10. gxf5 exf5 11. Qd2 { With a winning position. } 11... Nf7 12. Qf4 Ra2 13.
Qe3 Qe7 14. Bh3 Ng5 15. Bxf5 d4 16. Qxd4 Rxe2 17. Bxc8 Raa2 18. Nb2 Rxe5 19.
Rbd1 Re2 20. Rd2 Rxd2 21. Qxd2 Ne4 22. Qf4 Rxb2 23. Be6+ *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Durarbayli, Vasif vs. Gosdin, Kaleb Ryder"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp1bq1pp/1np1pb2/3pNp2/2PPnBP1/2NBP2P/PPQ2P2/2KR2R1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. c5 { A similar idea to that of Geller, albeit with opposite side castling. }
1... Nc8 2. f3 Nxc3 3. bxc3
{ The pawn on f5 is weak and White has very stable structure in the center, allowing the attack on the kingside. }
3... b6
{ There is no way to defend the pawn on f5 due to the pin on g-file. If   16...g6  17.Nxd7  Qxd7  18.gxf5  exf5  19.Bxf5  and wins }
4. gxf5 exf5 5. Nxd7 Qxd7 6. Bxf5 Qe7 7. Bxh7+
{ Now White is two pawns up and cruises through victory. } 7... Kh8 8. Bg6 Qd7
9. h4 Ne7 10. h5 Ng8 11. Qh2 Nh6 12. Bb1 bxc5 13. Qc2 g5 14. hxg6 Bg7 15. Bxh6
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Kholmov, Ratmir D vs. Lisitsin, Georgy M"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/p2n2pp/b1pqpn2/1p1p1p2/2PP4/1P3NP1/PQ1NPPBP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ I could have included this example into the Taking on e5 chapter but I think knowing how the sausage got made  (not to accuse M.Lisitsin of piggery, why I would never !)  is of utmost important in reaching the apex of action on either e5 or e4, just as tactics rely on construction, strategic themes depend on a series of previous decision and not just the one capture previously mentioned. }
1. c5 Qc7 2. Ne5 Nxe5 3. dxe5
{ Control of dark squares should be a familiar motif, by now. } 3... Nd7
{ Sometimes after dxe5, Black is able to exploit the weakening of c5 and e5 pawns, but here it is not the case. }
4. f4 Rce8 5. Nf3 Bc8 6. e3
{ Securing the center and stabilizing matters before starting kingside operations. }
6... Kh8 7. h3
{ Now White starts invading on the kingside and Black...waits for sweet Death to bring him home. }
7... Rg8 8. g4 Nf8 9. Kh1 Re7 10. Rg1 Bd7 11. Bf1
{ Going to the b1-h7 diagonal to exert maximum pressure. } 11... Be8 12. Bd3 g6
13. Rg3 Reg7 14. Rcg1
{ And White's attack plays itself. He already has a winning position. } 14...
Qe7 15. b4 Bd7 16. a4
{ Now that every Black piece got ready for the onslaught on the kingside, the enemy formations suddenly run to the deserted queenside. This is why we must value space so highly. }
16... a6 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ra1 h6 19. h4 fxg4 20. Rxg4 Be8 21. Qh2 Nh7 22. Nd4
Nf8 23. Rg2 Qf7 24. Ra6 Qc7 25. Rga2 Re7 26. Rb6 Qc8 27. Raa6 Rc7 28. Qa2 Qd8
29. Nf3 Qe7 30. Rb8 Nd7 31. Rba8 Bf7 32. Rxg8+ Kxg8 33. Rxc6
{ A cute little exchange sac : b4-c5 won't be stopped. } 33... Rxc6 34. Qa8+
Nb8 35. Qxb8+ Kg7 36. Bxb5 Rc7 37. Qb6 Ra7 38. Ba6 d4 39. exd4 g5 40. hxg5
{ Where is the bind ? Yep, on the dark squares ! Black bishop hates dark squares ! }
40... hxg5 41. d5 Rxa6 42. Qxa6 gxf4 43. d6 Qe8 44. Kg2 Qh8 45. Qc4 Qh6 46. Kf2
Bh5 47. d7 Bxf3 48. d8=Q Qh2+ 49. Kxf3 Qh1+ 50. Kxf4 Qh2+ 51. Kf3 Qh1+ 52. Ke2
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Bocharov, Dmitry vs. Bajarani, Ulvi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp1bq1pp/2pnpn2/3p1p2/2PP1N2/1P3NP1/P1Q1PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. c5 { This time White is starting a complete takeover on the queenside. }
1... Nf7
{ 15...Nde4  Looks more active, but the knight isn't doing anything there. White can continue just as in the game  16.Nd3  Rfc8  17.b4  with a dominating position }
2. Nd3
{ This is exactly what Black never wants to happen and why so many Stonewall are shown in classical positional manuals to illustrate bad bishops or color blindness. Obviously this could have been prevented by   
Not trading dark-squared bishops  and  Having prepared counterplay before White could have his knights on d3 and f3 to lock in the e-pawn. }
2... Rfc8
{ You can now play through the game at a faster pace, simply to remember the plan he uses and Black's tries. It's all pretty typical really. }
3. b4 a5 4. Rfb1 Be8 5. a4 axb4 6. Rxb4
{ And now with the b-file opened and the weak b7 pawn, the win is just a matter of time, so this is a good moment to stop the trainable variation and enjoy the rest of the game. }
6... Ra7 7. Qb2 Rca8 8. e3 Qc7 9. Bf1 Bd7 10. Nd2 Bc8 11. Nb3 Nd7 12. f4
{ Black bishop hates dark squares ! } 12... b6 13. cxb6 Nxb6 14. Ndc5 Nd8 15.
a5 Nd7 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 17. a6 Bc8 18. Nc5 Nf7 19. Rb6 Nd6 20. Qb4 Nc4 21. Bxc4
dxc4 22. Kf2 c3 23. Ke2 Qf7 24. Kd3 Qh5 25. Qxc3 Qxh2 26. Qb3 Kf7 27. Rb8 Qxg3
28. Rxc8 *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Kan, Ilia Abramovich vs. Batuev, Andrey Mikhailovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/pb2q1pp/1pp1p3/3pPp2/2PP4/1P1B4/P1QR1PPP/2R3K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. c5
{ Another locking-in of the poor Black bishop  (who hates what again ?)  . }
1... b5 2. b4
{ We can apply what we learned in the last chapters: the plan of a4-Ra1-Ra2 to put pressure on the queenside. }
2... Ra8 3. a4 a6 4. Qc3 Bc8 5. Ra2 Ra7 6. axb5 axb5 7. Rxa7 Qxa7 8. Ra1 Qc7 9.
Ra3 Bb7 10. Qa1
{ The way White got control over the a-file must be remembered, as he did everything right : trade the defender, attack the file with tempo, double with the strongest piece behind, which you want to do except if you intend the queen to go for mate. Now of course the first player is better. }
10... Rb8 11. Ra7 Qc8 12. Qa5 Ra8 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Qc7 Bc8 15. g4 g6 16. gxf5
gxf5 17. Qd8+ Kg7 18. h4 Qb7 19. h5 h6 20. Kf1 Qd7 21. Qf6+ Kg8 22. Qg6+ Kf8
23. Qxh6+ Qg7 24. Qf4
{ By some miracle of the human mind Black did not lose this but I think you may be convinced that he wouldn't repeat the experience given the chance, or we have encountered another masochist. }
24... Bd7 25. Be2 Be8 26. Bd1 Kg8 27. Qh4 Kh7 28. f4 Qa7 29. Kf2 Bf7 30. Qf6
Qd7 31. Be2 Qe8 32. Qg5 Qa8 33. Qf6 Qe8 34. Bf3 Qg8 35. Bd1 Qg7 36. Qg5 Qf8 37.
Kg3 Qg7 38. Kh4 Qh6 39. Be2 Qf8 40. Bd3 Qe8 41. Bf1 Qf8 42. Bg2 Be8 43. Qf6 Bf7
44. Bh3 Qe8 45. Bxf5+ exf5 46. Qxf5+ Kg8 47. Qg5+ Kh7 48. f5 Qh8 49. Kg4 *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Razuvaev, Yuri S vs. Short, Nigel D"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r1r1k/1ppqn1pp/4pbb1/p2p4/2PPP3/PP3BP1/1B1N2QP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

c5
{ Every time Black is playing against a trio of pawns on the fourth rank, this move should always be considered. The white knight on d2 give all the more reason to do so. }
2. Bg4
{ Capture on c5 obviously loses the bishop on b2, while taking on d5 is also bad:   22.exd5  exd5  23.cxd5  cxd4  and d5 pawn will soon be a goner }
2... Qc6 { Calmly sidestepping the pin. } 3. cxd5 exd5 4. e5 Bg5 5. Rxf8+
{ This exchange doesn't help, most probably. In some variations, it is to Black's benefit that he has control over the f-file, for example, in the line:   25.Qe2  Qb6  26.Nf3  Bh6  27.dxc5  Qxb3  28.Nd4  Qe3+  29.Qxe3  Bxe3+  30.Kg2  there is no check on f2. Although, of course, Black's play is not forced and he has better moves available }
5... Rxf8 6. Qe2 Qb6
{ White is not stable at all : once the d4 pawn goes away, Black's passed pawn in the centre will march to the end. The evidence that he shouldn't have given up the control over the f-file is provided by the variation:   27.Nf3  Bh6  28.dxc5  Qxb3  29.Nd4  Qe3+  30.Qxe3  Bxe3+  31.Kg2  and now, since his rook is on f-file, Black can play  31...Rf2+  winning on the spot. Compare this with the variation after 25 Rxf8 }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Privman, Boris vs. Jussupow, Artur"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/pb1nq1pp/1ppbpn2/3p1p2/1PPP4/3N2P1/PB1NPPBP/R1Q2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... c5
{ Black has to play this before White closes the queenside by playing c5 himself. }
2. dxc5
{ 14.cxd5  Taking on d5 is met with  14...cxd4  Discovering the attack on the queen  15.Qd1  e5  with tremendous center, weak pawn on d5 and winning position }
2... bxc5 3. bxc5
{ 15.b5  is sometimes a possible reaction, but here it is no good because Black's pieces are too active  e5  with the idea of e4. Black is simply better }
3... Nxc5 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 { And Black has a good position, e.g. } 5. Qa3 Qe7 6.
cxd5 Ne4 7. Qa5 Bxd5 8. Nf4 Rc5 { Black resigns as he loses a piece. } *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Epishin, Vladimir vs. Gabrielsen, Trond"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pppnb1pp/4pn2/3p1pB1/2PP4/4PN2/PPQN1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... c6
{ This move makes no sense in this structure, as the white light squared bishop is going to be developed in the center to d3. Here Black was duly punished. }
2. cxd5 cxd5
{ Black would rather take with the e-pawn but f5 is hanging. Now the c-file is an issue as Black can't hope for b6  (weakens c6)  or a kingside attack  (the invasion via c7 would be too fast)  . }
3. Be2 O-O 4. O-O h6 5. Bh4 g5 6. Bg3 Ne8 7. Rac1 Bf6 8. a4
{ The point is preventing Nb6 because of a5, or getting the b5 square in case of Black going a5 himself. }
8... Rf7 9. Nb3 { White redirects his knight towards the ideal square d3. }
9... Nf8 10. Nc5 Ng6 11. Nd3
{ With great control of the dark-squares and advantage on the queenside. White is close to winning already. }
11... Rg7 12. Nfe5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Nd6 14. Qb3 Ne4 15. Rc2 Bxe5 16. Nxe5 Rc7 17.
Rfc1 Rxc2 18. Rxc2 Nd6 19. Qa3 Nf7 20. Qb4 Nxe5 21. dxe5 Bd7 22. Qxb7 Rb8 23.
Qxa7 Ra8 24. Qb7 Rb8 25. Qa6 Rb6 26. Qa7 Bc6 27. a5 *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Yudovich, Mikhail Mikhailovic vs. Gusev, Yuri S"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/p1pnq1pp/bp1bp3/3p1p2/P1PPn3/NP3NP1/1BQ1PPBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

c6
{ Here on the other Black is taking c6 away from White's hands before doing his business on the kingside. With a knight on d7, Black usually prefers to attack on the kingside, compared to similar positions with a Na6. }
2. e3
{ 13.cxd5  as in the previous example, is bad here, due to  exd5!  14.Qxc6  Ndf6  with the threat of trapping the queen after ... Rc8  15.Qc2  Rfc8  16.Qd1  or else e2 pawn is lost  Nc3  with tremendous compensation for a pawn and almost a winning position }
2... Rac8 3. Rfd1 g5
{ 14...Ndf6  reinforcing the knight on e4 and heading toward g4, might be more circumspect, though }
4. Ne1 g4 5. Nd3 h5 { With a pleasant initiative for Black. } *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Leitao, Rafael Duailibe vs. Moraes, Nelson da Silva"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pb1nq1pp/1ppbpn2/3pNp2/1PPP1B2/P1N1P3/4BPPP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxc4
{ Black gives up the center with nothing to show for it. Now White enjoys himself on the light squares as Black doesn't even have the e4 square. }
2. Bxc4 Nd5 3. Nxd7 Qxd7 4. Bxd6 Qxd6 5. Qb3 Kh8 6. Rfe1 Rae8 7. Ne2
{ Black has all the structural weaknesses  (e5, e6, c6, f5)  . White can take on d5 and then play with a good knight against the bad bishop if he wants. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Landau, Salo vs. Kroone, Gerard"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1r1k/pp2b1pp/n1p1pn2/3p1p2/2PP4/PQ4PN/1P2PPBP/R1BR1NK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxc4
{ Black operates on a purely concrete basis to smash into the centre. } 2. Qxc4
{ 13.Qc2  b5  14.Bxc6  Rb8  with a double-edged middlegame. } 2... e5
{ Next Black goes e4 with a slight edge. } *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Krogius, Nikolai V vs. Zamikhovsky, Abram Davidovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1qrk1/pp1bb2p/2p1p3/3pPpn1/2PN2p1/1P1QP1P1/PB3PBP/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxc4
{ Again based on tactics, White has to recapture with the b pawn because of tactical problems on the light-squares. }
2. bxc4
{ Forced.   18.Qxc4  c5  19.Ne2   19.f4  doesn't work now:  19...cxd4  and the queen is under attack  Bc6  and after the exchange of light-squared bishops, ... Nf3 and ... Nh3 jumps will be incredibly strong and White is completely lost }
2... c5 3. Ne2
{ 19.f4  was a nice zwischenzug that offered some hope. After  cxd4  20.fxg5  dxe3  21.Qxe3  Bc6  there is no denying that Black is better, but White can keep resisting }
3... Bc6
{ Now White's light squares are getting torn to shred and he is completely lost. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Rakhmanov, Alexander vs. Potapov, Pavel"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3b1k1/4q2p/r1p1pn2/1pPpNp2/1P1P2p1/4P3/1QB2PPP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f3 { White has no reason to play on that side of the board. None ! } 1...
gxf3 2. Rxf3 Bh5 3. Rg3+ Bg4
{ Black is now better, compared to a situation where he had a dead bishop and much less space. He will eventually have a nice square on e4 for the knight  (after extricating himself from the pin. Note that)   26.h3  Doesn't work.  26...Nh5  and White loses an exchange }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Alatortsev, Vladimir vs. Chistiakov, Alexander Nikolaevi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r5rk/1p1bq1pp/2p1pn2/p3Np2/2PPp3/PP4P1/1Q2PPBP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f3
{ Here on the other hand, White is the only side who benefits from the opening of the position. }
1... exf3 2. Bxf3 Be8 3. c5
{ Creating the possibility of Nc4 and once again - taking control of the dark-squares on the queenside. }
3... g5 4. Bg2 Qg7 5. e4
{ A good move, opening the position in White's favour. } 5... Bg6
{ Black can't take the pawn.   21...fxe4  is met strongly in a tactical fashion.  22.Rxf6!   22.Rce1  is more prosaic  Qxf6  23.d5  creating a tremendous threat of Nf7/Ng6  23...Qg7  24.Rf1  with a terrible threat of Rf7  exd5  25.Rf7  and wins  while after   21...Nxe4  the same tactic works  22.Bxe4  fxe4  23.d5  h6  24.dxe6  and White is winning }
6. exf5 exf5 7. Rce1
{ Black would never dream of opening the kingside since the a1-h8 diagonal is not secure. Too many dark squares  (b6-d6-e5)  are weak for White not to be seriously better and he has a choice of whether to come through the e-file or target the a5 pawn, among others. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Akobian, Varuzhan vs. Shulman, Yuri"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pppbb2p/4pn2/2PpNpp1/3Pn3/3BP1B1/PP2NPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f3 { Getting rid of the only good Black piece. } 1... Nxg3 2. hxg3 Be8 3. g4
Nd7
{ Taking on g4 was also not inspiring. After   15...fxg4  16.Qc2!  White has tremendouns compensation for the pawn and wants to play ...f4 next, opening the position up completely }
4. Qc2 Bg6 5. c6 Nxe5 6. dxe5 b6 7. Nd4
{ This is horrible. Black is never ever in time to stabilize the centre, the triangle d5-e6-f5 is under constant attack, and you may consider the interesting move Kf2 so as to let the rooks invade the h-file. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Szabo, Laszlo vs. Gereben, Erno"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp1bb1pp/2p1p3/3p4/2PPp3/1P3PP1/P3P1BP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ f3 is not as attractive for White when the centre is not well defended, especially when bishops are involved. }
1... exf3 2. Bxf3 dxc4 3. bxc4 e5 4. d5
{ White can't really capture the pawn on e5   15.dxe5  Bc5+  16.Kh1  Bh3  17.Re1  Qe7  and Black has great compensation for the pawn   15.Bb2  developing and trying to reinforce the center was maybe the best move in the position. The point is to meet  15...Bh3  with  16.Rf2 }
4... Bh3 5. Re1 Bc5+ 6. e3 Bb4
{ Here Black simply wins material as the rook is trapped and Re2 or Bd2 would drop the f3-bishop. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Keres, Paul vs. Richter, Kurt Paul"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1q1r1k/pb4pp/1ppb4/3pN3/3P1B2/1Q3pP1/PP2P1BP/R2R2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. exf3
{ Given the option, you should almost always recapture with a pawn on f3. e4 and the e-file in general are way too valuable to pass on. Here Black is much worse since he's way behind in development and will suffer on c6  (c5 would allow dxc5 and an assault on the d5 pawn)  . The e-file is where the invasion will most likely start. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Flohr, Salo vs. Botvinnik, Mikhail Moisevich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1nb1pp/2p5/3p1p1q/3P4/1PBQ1PP1/P2NP1BP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... f4 { Black will now rip through the kingside. } 2. Rfe1 Bd6 3. Nf1 Rf7
{ Black wants to play Nf8-Ng6, increasing the pressure on the dark-squares. }
4. e3 { It is hard to suggest a plan for White. } 4... fxg3 5. Nxg3 Qh4 6. Nf1
Nf6
{ 19...Nf8  was equally good, but as it is, Black gained a strong attack and went on to win convincingly. }
7. Re2 Bd7 8. Be1 Qg5 9. Bg3 Bxg3 10. Nxg3 h5 11. f4 Qg4 12. Rf2 h4 13. Bf3
{ Now a simple combination follows. } 13... hxg3 14. Bxg4 gxf2+ 15. Kg2 Nxg4
16. h3 Nf6 17. Kxf2 Ne4+
{ Black is absolutely winning with a thousand pieces to White's queen. It is important that the knight has a nice outpost on e4, from where it can't be removed. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Fridman, Daniel vs. Sotsky, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1nq1pp/2p1p3/3p4/2PP1N2/5BP1/PPQ1P2P/4RRK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... e5 { Now or never ! White is going to play Nd3 and e4 otherwise. } 2. dxe5
Qc5+ 3. Kg2 Nxe5 4. b3 Bf5 5. Qc3
{ It was also possible to maintain the tension for the moment and include the rook immediately with   19...Rae8  with the idea of going b5 }
5... d4 6. Qd2 Rae8
{ White's pieces can't go anywhere and he's the only one with weaknesses which happen to be on the open e-file. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Forintos, Gyozo Victor vs. Honfi, Karoly"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2r1k/pp2q1pp/2p1p3/2Pp1p2/2nP1P2/1QN3P1/PP2PKBP/R6R b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... e5 { An undefended centre calls for this kind of measure ! } 2. fxe5
{ 16.dxe5  would drop the c5 pawn:  16...Qxc5+  and Black is winning } 2... f4
{ The king on f2 is a clear target! } 3. Kg1 Nxe5
{ The cleanest. Now White collapses completely in the centre. } 4. Rf1
{ 18.dxe5  loses.  18...Qxc5+  19.Kf1  fxg3+  20.Ke1  Qf2+  21.Kd1  Qxg2 } 4...
Ng6
{ And Black has a devastating attack. A good moment to end the trainable line. }
5. Rf2 Qe3 6. Nd1 Qxd4 7. gxf4 Qxc5 8. e3 Bg4 9. Rc2 Nxf4 10. Nf2 Ne2+ 11. Kf1
Qe7 12. Rxe2 Bxe2+ 13. Kxe2 Qh4 14. Rf1 Qh5+ 15. Ke1 Qxh2 16. Bh3 Rae8 17. Bd7
Re7 18. Qa3 Ref7 19. e4 Qh4 20. Kd1 Qd8 *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Erdos, Viktor vs. Mazur, Stefan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/2q3pp/b1p1p3/p1PpN3/1p1Pp3/1P2P1P1/PQ3P1P/R3R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. a3
{ Having closed the center and guaranteed supremacy over queenside with c5, White now gets dirty on the a5 pawn. }
1... bxa3
{ If Black decides to wait with   22...Rfb8  then White doubles on the a-file nevertheless.  23.Ra2  Rb7  24.Rea1  and will take on b4 himself }
2. Rxa3 Bb5 3. Rea1 Ra7 4. Qd2 Rfa8 5. h4
{ Starting operations on the kingside. White is clever and will move around with his king a couple of moves to lure Black into a false sense of safety. }
5... Qd8 6. R3a2 Qc7 7. Kg2 Qd8 8. Kh2 Qc7 9. Qd1 Qd8 10. Kg1 Qf6 11. Qh5 Rf8
12. Qg5 Rfa8 13. Ng4 Qf8 14. h5 Kh8 { And here White should have continued }
15. h6 Qf5 16. hxg7+ Rxg7 17. Qxf5 exf5 18. Ne5 Rga7 19. Kg2
{ Now White will slide over to the h-file with his rooks. Black can't defend a5, c6, f5 and h7 at the same time. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Fressinet, Laurent vs. Kosten, Anthony C"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qb1k1/1pp3pp/p1n4r/3p1p2/1P1Pn3/P2BPN2/2Q2PPP/R1R1B1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. a4 Bh5 2. Be2 Qd6
{ Now White would be winning if not for Black's initiative on the kingside. How to put it to a halt ? }
3. h3
{ 18.g3 ?  Possibly missing or underestimating Black's next move, was seen in the game.  f4  19.b5  fxg3  20.fxg3  Qf6  21.Qd1  Nd8  22.bxa6  bxa6  23.Ne5  Bxe2  24.Qxe2  Qd6  followed by c5 with equality. }
3... Bg4
{ 18...g5  is too slow and White gets his initiative first with  19.b5  axb5  20.axb5 }
4. hxg4 fxg4 5. Ne5 Nxe5 6. Qxc7
{ illustrates the inefficiency of Black's offensive. It's just too slow ! } *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Chekhover, Vitaly A vs. Riumin, Nikolay Nikolaevich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qrk1/pp4pp/2p2b2/1P1p1p2/P1nP4/2N1PNP1/2Q2PBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. a5
{ Black has no e-pawn to throw at White's centre, the first player has all the time in the world to operate on his side. }
1... a6 2. bxc6 bxc6 3. Nd2 { Removing the strong c4 knight. } 3... Nxd2
{ 18...Nd6  is not much better. White continues with his initiative  19.Na4 }
4. Qxd2 Ra7 5. Rab1
{ 20.Na4  heading to c5, is also possible. In any case, White has a very pleasant position. }
5... Kh8 6. Na4 g5 7. Nc5
{ Black has too many weaknesses to create counterplay, especially lacking a knight to go to e4 is a huge issue. He's just much worse. }
7... Bd8 8. Nd3 h5 9. Rfc1 Rh7 { Too late, too slow... } 10. Bxd5 cxd5 11. Rxc8
h4 12. Rbb8 hxg3 13. fxg3 Rd7 14. Ne5 f4 15. exf4 gxf4 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Qxf4 *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Steiner, Herman vs. Botvinnik, Mikhail Moisevich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1nb1pp/2p1pn2/3p1p1q/2PP1B2/2N3P1/PPQNPPBP/4RRK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

g5
{ Black's stealthy attack is a model for this kind of strategy. Notice how the knight on d2 allows g5 to be played at once and the importance of trading the White dark-squared bishop for the offensive to be successful. }
2. Bc7 Ne8 3. Be5 Nxe5 4. dxe5 f4 5. gxf4 gxf4 6. Nf3 Kh8 7. Kh1 Ng7
{ Black is going to improve all his pieces and attack on the kingside because his centre is very stable. }
8. Qc1 Bd7 9. a3 Rf7 10. b4 Rg8 11. Rg1 Nf5 12. Nd1 Rfg7
{ Very instructive play. Black has a decisive attack and the pawn on f4 shouldn't concern him at all. }
13. Qxf4 Rg4 14. Qd2 Nh4 15. Ne3 Nxf3 16. exf3 Rh4 17. Nf1 Bg5 *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Ehlvest, Jaan vs. Rapport, Richard"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/ppp1b1pp/2n1p3/3p1p2/2PPn3/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

h5
{ Rapport's plan is an interesting wrinkle on typical Stonewall practice. The combination of Ne4, not castling and playing h5 looks dubious but brings great results to the Hungarian. Perhaps White should wait for Black to castle before he does so himself to frustrate this idea ? For my part, I have been unable to clearly refute Black's concept... }
2. Nbd2 h4 3. Rc1 hxg3 4. hxg3
{ 11.fxg3  gives another target on the e3 square. } 4... Bf6
{ 11...Bd6  Giving Black the option of Qf6-h6 is more efficient as White may soon land blows on the queenside. }
5. e3
{ 12.a3  first would prevent the next note's idea and prepare Qc2, b4, b5 to play on the c-file. Still Black is not worse here either after for instance  a5 }
5... Qe7
{ 12...Nb4 !  Just grabbing a pawn, is the computer's first choice, though not really linked to Rapport's intentions. }
6. cxd5
{ 13.Ne5  Bxe5  14.dxe5  Bd7  with long castling is very promising for Black as well. }
6... exd5 7. Rxc6 { Desperation. } 7... bxc6 8. Qc1 Qe6 9. Qc2 Ba6 10. Re1 g5
11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 g4 13. Nf1 Rh6
{ White resigns since he is material down and on the road to being mated. } *


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Riazantsev, Alexander vs. Rapport, Richard"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pp1nb1pp/2pnp3/3p1p2/P1PP4/1PN3P1/3NPPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... h5
{ This version of h5 looks inferior at first glance since Black's pieces are not crashing fast but White didn't manage to get to the queenside in the game. }
2. b4
{ 11.h4  g5  12.hxg5  Bxg5  13.Nf3  Bf6  14.Bf4  Nf8 !  with Ng6 and h4 is also a mess, computers prefer White but I would assume most humans do not. }
2... h4 3. b5 hxg3 4. hxg3 Nf6 5. Qb3
{ Rapport won this game after further adventures but here the natural } 5...
Nfe4 { already gives Blacks a comfortable plus. } 6. Ndxe4 fxe4
{ For once we take back this way since e6 is safe and we need something to be present on d5 to keep our centered king safe. }
*


[White "Other changes in the pawn structure"]
[Black "Gruenfeld, Ernst vs. Vajda, Arpad"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pb1qb1pp/1pp1n3/3p1p2/3P4/P1N1P1P1/1PQ2PBP/R1BR2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... h5
{ About a century ago another Hungarian had tried the same concept with success ! }
2. h4 g5 3. hxg5 Nxg5 4. Ne2 Rf7 5. Bd2 Rh7 6. Bb4 h4
{ Now Black is ready to stew White's entrails from the kingside. This is a good moment to end the trainable variation, as the h4 push is the main strategical idea in this position. }
7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. Qxf5 h3 9. Bh1 h2+
{ Now Black embarks on the final combination. } 10. Kf1 Rf8 11. Qe5 Qd8
{ Of course, Black doesn't want to exchange queens in a position like this. Apart from the weak white king, his lady is also surprisingly exposed on e5. }
12. Rac1 Rhf7 13. g4 { 30.f4  Re8  And the queen is trapped. } 13... Rxf2+ 14.
Ke1 Ba6
{ And White decided to throw in the towel as he gets checkmated very soon. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Capablanca, Jose Raul vs. Botvinnik, Mikhail Moisevich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqnr1k/pp1n2pp/2p1pb2/2Pp1p2/3P1B2/1QNNP1P1/PP3PBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's start this chapter with a very one-sided example. Black is much worse due to the passivity and lack of prospects for his knights. White starts regrouping around the e5 square. }
1. Ne2
{ The knight leaves its places to the queen, as it can't immediately fight for the main target on e5. }
1... Qe7 2. Qc3 g5 3. Be5 Nxe5 4. dxe5 Bg7 5. f4
{ All Black pieces are terrible here. With a fixed structure, the knights are much stronger than Black's bishops and even the steed on e8 is horrendous. }
5... Nc7 6. a4 Bd7 7. Nd4 Rg8 8. Kf2 Be8 9. Qb4 Na6 10. Qa5 Bd7 11. Rfc1 Rgc8
12. Bf1 Bf8 13. Qc3 Qg7 14. b4 Be7
{ Here the cleanest way to expand on the queenside would be } 15. Ne1
{ threatening to take on a6 or play b5 if the knight leaves its post. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Petrosian, Tigran V vs. Pirtskhalava, A.."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1nq1pp/2pbpn2/3p1p2/2PP4/1PN2NP1/PB2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Please remember the White manoeuvring with his knights : it is the standard and optimal plan in this structure. }
1. e3 Ne4 2. Ne2
{ Black should start creating counterplay on the queenside with b6 and a5-a4 here. Instead she goes on the wrong side of the board. }
2... Qf6 3. Nf4 Qh6 4. Nd3
{ 13.h4 !  to safeguard the knight may have been even better. As it was, White proceeded to outplay his opponent by blowing up the centre. }
4... Ndf6 5. Nfe5
{ This is White's ideal setup, particularly when Black has gone all-in on the kingside and can't counterstrike through c5 efficiently. }
5... Ng5 6. f3 Nf7 7. Qe2 g5 8. Rae1 a5 9. e4 Bb4 10. Rd1 dxe4 11. fxe4 Nxe5
12. dxe5 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 fxe4 14. Nf2 Bc5 15. Bd4 Be7 16. Nxe4 Bd7 17. Bc5 Rxf1+
18. Rxf1 Bxc5+ 19. Nxc5 Be8 20. Rf6 Bg6 21. Nxe6 g4 22. Nf4 Qg5 23. Nxg6 hxg6
24. Rf4 Kg7 25. Qe3 Qd8 26. e6 Qe8 27. Rf7+ *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Keres, Paul vs. Botvinnik, Mikhail Moisevich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5r1k/ppr3pp/2b1pn2/3p1p2/3P1P2/P1N5/1P2PPBP/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

Rfc8
{ Once White has traded on d5, the c-file is absolutely critical. Black is the getting it here. }
2. e3
{ Black suddenly gets a great bishop instead of a tamed one, but the main point is that the only open file falls into Black's hands for good.   25.Na2  Bb5  26.Rxc7  Rxc7  27.Rc1  Rxc1+  28.Nxc1  would alleviate the pressure along the c-file.   25.Rb1  Ne8  would be similar to the game. }
2... Bb5 3. Rfe1 Kg8 4. f3 Bc4 5. Bf1 Ne8 6. Bxc4 Rxc4 7. Kf2 Nd6 8. Ke2 b5 9.
Kd3 b4 10. Na2 bxa3 11. bxa3 Ra4 12. Rxc8+ Nxc8 13. Nc3 Rxa3
{ Black is now a pawn to the good and converted without too much trouble. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Flohr, Salo vs. Szabo, Laszlo"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb2rk1/pp2b1pp/2p1pn2/3p1p1q/2PP4/P1N2NP1/1PQBPPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Na2 Nbd7 2. Bb4
{ Trading the dark squared bishop is often a very potent strategy for White, for two reasons : White's bishop only use would be to control the e5 square, which is typically controlled by at least three other pieces  (d4, Nf3 and the soon to come Nd3)  . Its Black counterpart is perfect to prepare e5, c5 or even g5. Simply put, this is a case of bad bishop traded for good bishop. }
2... Re8 3. Bxe7 Rxe7 4. Nb4 Ng4 5. Nd3 { Black has zero counterplay. } 5... g5
6. e3 Rg7 7. h3 Ngf6 8. Nfe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Nd7 10. Nd3 Nf8 11. Rac1 Ng6 12. Qd1
{ This is not forced by any stretch, in fact one would argue that trading pieces when being in command of the position may not be the optimal strategy. Still, the endgame is very promising for White, especially in one of the very best endgame players who ever lived.   22.Rfe1  Bd7  23.Qb3  f4  24.Nc5  Bc8  25.exf4  gxf4  26.g4  shows how powerless Black is. }
12... Qxd1 13. Rfxd1 Kf8
{ 23...f4  24.exf4  gxf4  25.g4  is still much better for White. } 14. Bf3 Ke7
15. Kf1 Bd7 16. Ke2 Rf8 17. Rh1 Kd6 18. h4
{ 28.c5+  Kc7  29.Bh5  Prepares a new trade to control e5 for good and guarantee a good knight vs bad bishop situation. }
18... gxh4 19. gxh4 Rfg8
{ 29...e5  still favours White but at least Black has some counterplay. } 20.
h5
{ The rest of the game is stellar techinque against this precise structure. }
20... dxc4 21. Nc5 Ne7 22. Nxb7+ Kc7 23. Nc5 Kd6 24. Rxc4 Rb8 25. Rc2 Be8 26.
Nd3 Nd5 27. Ne5 h6 28. Rhc1 Ne7 29. b4 Rg5 30. Rc5 Rb5 31. R5c2 Bxh5 32. Rh1
Bxf3+ 33. Kxf3 Rxe5 34. dxe5+ Kxe5 35. Rxh6 Rg1 36. Rc5+ Kd6 37. Ra5 Ng6 38.
Rxa7 Ne5+ 39. Ke2 Ra1 40. Rh4 Ra2+ 41. Kf1 Ng4 42. Rxg4 fxg4 43. Kg2 Ra1 44. a4
Rb1 45. Rb7 Ra1 46. a5 c5 47. bxc5+ Kxc5 48. Ra7 Kd5 49. a6 Ke4 50. Ra8 Kd3 51.
Kg3 Ke2 52. a7 Ra4 53. e4 Kf1 54. e5 Ke2 55. Re8 Rxa7 56. Rxe6 Ra4 57. Re8 Kd3
58. e6 Ke4 59. Kxg4 Ke5+ 60. Kg5 Rf4 61. Ra8 Rf5+ 62. Kg4 *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Birjanis vs. Tal, Mihail"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp4pp/2pbpnqn/3p1pN1/2PP1P2/PPN1P1PP/1B1Q2B1/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

Nf7
{ Black prepares this trade to open the kingside up through g5 and generate an attack. }
2. Nxf7
{ 16.h4  seems more natural, reinforcing the knight, but after  16...h6  White is forced to trade on f7 all the same, and he has weakened light-squares on the kingside. g5 plan is still coming and Black is significantly better }
2... Rxf7 3. Qf2 Qh6
{ 17...b6  would actually be a better preparation with Bb7 and Ba6. } 4. Rac1
g5 5. c5
{ A terrible strategic decision, closing the side where White was supposed to play. Although Black's play is not perfect from here  (especially Bd8-e7)  , he always benefits from a terrible initiative. }
5... Bc7 6. b4 Rg7 { All of Black's pieces are ready to rage on the kingside. }
7. b5 gxf4 8. exf4 Nh5 9. Ne2 Bd8 10. Rc3 Bd7 11. bxc6 Bxc6 12. Kh2 Kh8 13. Rg1
Be7 14. Bc1 Rag8
{ Black has achieved the optimal position of his pieces. Mikhail Tal has needed less to win chess games so the outcome is predictable. }
15. Re3 Bb5 16. Re1 Nxg3 17. Nc3 { 31.Nxg3  Bh4 } 17... Ne4 18. Bxe4 Bh4 19.
Qc2 Bxe1 20. Rxe1 fxe4 21. Qf2 Bd7 *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Piket, Jeroen vs. Timman, Jan H"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qrk1/pp1n2pp/2pbp3/3p1p2/2PPnN2/1P3NP1/P1Q1PPBP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nd3 { A typical maneuver we have already seen in several instances. } 1...
Qh5 2. Nfe5
{ This is the ideal placing of knights for White, in order to oust Black's e4 steed. }
2... Nxe5 3. dxe5
{ 14.Nxe5  is also possible here, but taking with the pawn is even better! }
3... Be7 4. f3 Nc5 5. Ba3 b6 6. Nxc5 bxc5 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Bxc5
