[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Keres, Paul vs. Maslov, Leonid P"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rr3k/1b2b1pp/1pp1n1q1/3pPp2/1P6/1QNBPP2/1B4PP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ne2 { The main weakness on f5 is easily targeted. } 1... Rc7 2. Ng3 Rf8 3.
Nxf5
{ The knight is taboo due the pin being exploited through Qc2 and g4. Now the kingside gets flooded like a 19th century Paris apartment  (trust me, that's bad) }
3... Bd8 4. Nd6 Qh6 5. f4
{ And White has such an overwhelming position, the rest doesn't require any special commentary. }
5... c5 6. Bb1 c4 7. Qc2 c3 8. Bc1 d4 9. exd4 Bd5 10. Rd3 Nxf4 11. Rxf4 Rxf4
12. Rh3 Be4 13. Nxe4 Rcf7 14. Bxf4 Qxf4 15. Rf3 *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Makogonov, Vladimir Andreevich vs. Kofman, Rafael Moiseevich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1rbq1rk1/p5pp/4pn2/3n1p2/1bNP4/4PPPN/PB5P/R2QRBK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ba3 { White trades Black's best. } 1... Bxe1 2. Qxe1
{ A very promising exchange sacrifice. White dominates the dark-squares. } 2...
Rf7 3. Rc1
{ White goes e4, Bd6 and Ne5. The dark squares complex under his hands more than compensates for the sacrificed exchange. He is close to strategically winning. }
