[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Uhlmann, Wolfgang vs. Guimard, Carlos Enrique"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp1nbbpp/2p1pn2/3p1pN1/2PP4/BPN2PP1/P3P1BP/R1Q2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Bxa3
{ I know, I know, we're not supposed to trade our dark squared bishop as Black. Here, though, there is a tactical justification based on the random placement of White's knights. }
2. Qxa3 dxc4 3. bxc4 Nb6
{ Both c4 and d4 are under attack and there is only one way of defending them. }
4. Qc5 Nfd7 5. Nxf7 Qf6
{ A great zwischenzug, keeping the queen and the d4 pawn under attack. } 6. Qd6
Rxf7 7. c5 Nc4 8. Qf4 g5 { White will lose the house. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Bisguier, Arthur Bernard vs. Robinson, Nathan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qrk1/pp2b1pp/2p1pn2/3p1p2/2PPn3/BP2PNP1/P2N1PBP/R1Q2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxe7 Qxe7 2. Ne5 Nd7 3. Ndf3 { This is identical to Flohr's game. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Razuvaev, Yuri S vs. Moraza, Manuel"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r1r2k1/ppq1nbpp/2p1p3/2N2p2/PP1PP3/5PP1/2Q3BP/2RR2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bh3 g6 2. Bf1 { The e6 pawn is a zombie after Bc4 and Qa2. } 2... Rbc8 3.
Qb2 { Protecting Black's only target on d4 before relocating the knight. } 3...
b6 { This was impossible earlier due to the fork on a6. } 4. Nd3 Qb8 5. Ne5 Qb7
6. Bc4 { The e6 pawn will fall sooner or later. } 6... Rd6 7. Rd2 Rcd8 8. Re1
a6 9. Qa2 Kg7 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Bxe6+ Rxe6 12. exf5
{ The culmination of White's strategy against the e6 point. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Melkumyan, Hrant vs. Grischuk, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb2rk1/p1p3pp/1p1q4/3p1p2/3Pn3/1P2PNP1/P4PBP/RN1Q1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Ba6 2. Re1 Nd7 3. Qc1 c5
{ The dark-squared bishops trade is not as detrimental to Black's chances if he can prepare levers on those very same dark squares. }
4. Qa3 Bb7 5. dxc5 bxc5 { With a good position with hanging pawns. } 6. Nbd2
Ndf6 7. Rad1 Ng4 8. Nc4
{ Taking on e4 would merely help Black open the f-file   18.Nxe4  fxe4  19.Ng5  Rxf2  and wins!  Defending f2 was most resistant:   18.Rf1  but Black can simply continue improving his pieces with  18....a5  and White can never chase the knight from g2 away due to  19.h3  Ngxf2!  20.Rxf2  Qxg3  21.Re2  Nc3  with decisive advantage }
8... Qe7 9. Na5 Ngxf2 { White is crushed. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Barkhagen, Jonas vs. Jussupow, Artur"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r5rk/pp1b3p/2p2q2/2Qp1pp1/3P1P2/4PN2/PP3P1P/R4R1K b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Be8 { A move signaling the typical transfer of the bishop to h5. } 2. Ne5
Bh5 { Next is Rae8xe5, so White has to act against this plan with } 3. f3 g4 4.
fxg4 fxg4 { White has to quickly go to defence mode with } 5. Qc2 Rg7
{ Interestingly, White's central structure is itself a Stonewall, which makes the present situation even more double-edged than usual, particularly after a move like f5. }
*


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Vernersson, Per vs. Karlsson, Lars"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1pp1qb1p/3b4/3p1pp1/pP1Pn3/3NPNP1/1PQ2PBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Be8
{ The previous manoeuvre can also be used to transfer from the kingside to the queenside when the light squares have been softened there. e8 will always be the ideal platform for going back and forth with the bishop. }
2. Nc5 Bb5 3. Rfe1 c6 { The b4 pawn is falling after a timely b6. } 4. Nxa4 g4
5. Nh4 Bxb4 6. Red1 Rae8 { Black is dominating. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Taimanov, Mark E vs. Fichtl, Jiri"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp1q2pp/2bb4/3p1p2/3N4/1Q2PP2/PP1B2PP/1KR4R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bb4 { Look at how Taimanov exploits the victimhood of the c6-bishop. } 1...
Bxb4 2. Qxb4
{ Now we have a clear-cut example of good knight against bad bishop with an isolated pawn. Usually trading the bishop of the opposite squares of the isolani is an excellent strategy. }
2... Rac8 3. g3 h6 4. Rc3 Rf6 5. Rhc1 Kh7 6. Qa3 a6 7. Rc5 h5 8. Qd3 g6 9. a4
Rd6 10. b4 b6 11. R5c3 Bb7 12. Rxc8 Bxc8 13. Qc2 Bb7 14. Qc7 *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Laznicka, Viktor vs. Kindermann, Stefan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pp2b1p1/2p1pn1p/3p1p2/2PP1B2/6PN/PPQNPPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxb8 Rxb8 2. Nf4
{ Here an important detail is the weakened g6 square, from which White can physically prevent g5 and access to e5. }
*


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Sasikiran, Krishnan vs. Moskalenko, Viktor"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/p2nq1pp/bppbp3/3p1p2/2PPnB2/1P1N1NP1/P1Q1PPBP/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Bxf4
{ As previously written, being able to sprout our levers makes the trade perfectly fine. }
2. Nxf4 { 15.gxf4  is met with the undermining  15...c5 } 2... g5 3. Nd3 c5
{ Black has the initiative. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Geisser, E. vs. Capablanca, Jose Raul"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pbpn2pp/1p3b2/3p1p2/3Pn3/1PNBPN2/PB2QPPP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ba6
{ We'll trade the light squared bishops in order to target c6 and d5 easily. Notice that a knight on e5 is just next door. }
*


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Magar, Thomas P vs. Ehlvest, Jaan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4r1k/1bpn2pp/p2b1q2/4pp2/1p1P4/1B2PP2/PP2Q1PP/2RRBNK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ba4 { The same idea in other surroundings. } 1... Nb6 2. Bc6 Bxc6 3. Rxc6
{ White is now threatening to trade on e5 and activate his rook, so Black closes the centre }
3... e4
{ But White now kills off any potential counterplay and begins collecting the weaknesses. }
4. Bg3 Nd5 5. fxe4 fxe4 6. Nd2
{ And Black is somewhat worse. He has a clear weakness on e4 and White's rooks are more potent, but he does have a good knight on d5. }
*


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Flohr, Salo vs. Menchik, Vera"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp5p/2p1pn2/2Pp1ppq/1PnP4/4PNP1/P1Q1NPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nc1
{ Here Flohr conducts an identical combo of ideas to the one we saw earlier in this chapter. }
1... Bd7 2. Nd3 Rae8 3. Qd1 Re7 4. Nfe5 Qxd1 5. Rfxd1 Nxe5 6. Nxe5
{ 20.dxe5  is also possible } 6... Be8 7. a4 Nd7 8. Nxd7 Bxd7 9. f4
{ The endgame is horrendous for Black. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Simagin, Vladimir Pavlovich vs. Chistiakov, Alexander Nikolaevi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qrk1/pp1nb1pp/2p1pn2/3p1p2/2PP4/1PN2NP1/PB2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. e3
{ When Black want to invade on the kingside or is underdeveloped, White should play e3-Ne2 in order to get to f4 as fast as possible. In general, in d4-d5 structures, a knight is at its best on d3 for White and d6 for Black. }
1... Ne4 2. Ne2 a5 3. Nf4 Ndf6 4. Ne5
{ Again the ideal setup for White. Never let that happen without b6-c5 available right up if you're Black ! }
4... a4 5. bxa4 g5 6. Nfd3 g4 7. h3 gxh3 8. Bxh3 Kh8 9. Nf4 Rg8 10. Bg2
{ This last move prevents Black's last idea on the kingside } 10... h5 11. Bf3
h4 12. Kg2 { You should be able to find out who is mating whom now. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Hansen, Eric vs. Lenderman, Aleksandr"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/1b1n2pp/1pp2n2/p2p1p2/3P4/NP3NP1/P3PPBP/R1R3K1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nc2
{ The c-file is the key point of the fight, most of all the c5 square. Usually, if Black is able to play c5 he will be fine, which is why Nc2-e1-d3 is the most logical manoeuvre. }
1... Ne4
{ The immediate push of the c-pawn does not equalize:   15...c5  16.dxc5  bxc5  17.Nce1  and the hanging pawns are rather a weakness, since f5 pawn is also exposed and White has a grip on the dark-squares once again, for example:  17...Ke7  18.Nd3  Kd6  19.Nf4  Rhe8  20.Rc2  and the hanging pawns on b5 and c5 are more of a liability than an asset }
2. Nce1 Ke7 3. Nd3 Rhc8 4. Rc2 c5 5. Rac1
{ White is in perfect control. Bh3 and g4 ideas are coming next. } 5... a4 6.
Bh3 g6 7. g4
{ Another key idea to remember, as the h3-c8 diagonal is soft through the f5-pawn. }
7... axb3 8. axb3
{ Black's clearest equalizer was here. When saddled with the worst long-term prospects  (here a worse structure)  , you have to play for activity and seek the most direct ideas. }
8... Kf6
{ Although Black may not be lost yet, it is hard to pinpoint where exactly he becomes so.   22...c4 !  concretely equalizes.  23.bxc4  dxc4  24.Rxc4  Rxc4  25.Rxc4  Nd6  26.Rc1  Bxf3  27.exf3  Nb5 }
9. gxf5 gxf5 10. Nf4 Rg8+ 11. Kf1
{ Now White is clearly playing for two results and Black quickly collapsed. }
11... Ra3 12. Nh5+ Ke6 13. Nh4 Nd6 14. Ng3 Rg5 15. Rc3 cxd4 16. Rc7 Rxb3 17.
Nhxf5 *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Arkell, Keith C vs. Agdestein, Simen"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pppbb1pp/2n1p3/3nNp2/3P4/1P4P1/P3PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxd7
{ This trade, seemingly illogical  (best knight for worst bishop)  is justified by the fact that the centre is already half open and will be opened further, which gives the better prospects to the fianchettoed bishops. }
*


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Sokolov, Ivan vs. Rasidovic, Sead"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppbn2pp/2p1p3/3p1p2/1PPPn3/3N2P1/PB1NPPBP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black should always try to find some squares for his knights, almost always on the light squares  (c4-d5-e4-f5)  . But White controls those squares so trades are often necessary. }
1... Nxd2 2. Qxd2 Nb6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Qc2 Nc4
{ As advertised, all light squares are in Black's pocket. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Agdestein, Simen vs. Karlsson, Lars"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1q1rk1/p5pp/bpp1p3/3pNp2/2PPnB2/2P3P1/P1Q1PPBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Nd6 { Black is fighting for the c4 square again. } 2. cxd5 cxd5 3. Rfe1
Nc4
{ The same strategy is only good enough for equality this time due to White's lever on e4. }
4. Nd3 Nc6 5. f3
{ This is the best reaction. There is now approximate equality with weakened squares compensated by the bishop pair. }
*


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Fedorovsky, Michael vs. Adams, Michael"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r2k1/1b1nqrpp/3b4/pBpp1p2/4n3/1P2PNN1/P1Q2PPP/B1RR2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Nf8
{ Usually one knight will have an outpost. What about the second one ? Well, it helps prepare levers in the ideal situation. }
2. Nh5 Ng6 3. Qe2 f4 4. exf4 Nxf4 5. Nxf4 Bxf4 6. Rc2 Rdf8
{ White is going to get smashed on the kingside. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Zubov, Alexander vs. Zhigalko, Andrey"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1bpn2pp/pp1bp2q/P4p2/2PPn3/2NBPN1P/1B2QPP1/R1R3K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Rf6
{ When White places most of his pieces on the queenside, a rook lift must be considered. Notice that the dc4 trade happened to help the light-squared bishop target the g2 pawn. }
2. Bxe4 fxe4 3. Nh2 Rg6 4. Kh1 Rf8 5. Ba3 c5
{ 19...Rf3  now doesn't work due to  20.Bxd6  eliminating an important attacker }
6. Rg1 { 20.axb6  loses on the spot to  20...Rf3  21.Rg1  Rxg2! } 6... Qh4 7.
Raf1 Nf6
{ The attack has reached its apex...  see next bit !   21...Rf3  was even stronger. }
8. Nd1 Bxh2
{ Trading a terrible piece...but it's worth it as now the White king is stripped bare ! }
9. Kxh2 Ng4+ 10. Qxg4 Rxg4 { And Black should win easily. } 11. axb6 Rg5 12.
Bxc5 Rxc5 13. dxc5 Qh5 *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Nyback, Tomi vs. Nisipeanu, Liviu Dieter"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r5k1/1pp3pp/p1nq1n2/3p3b/1P1P1r2/P4N2/1B1QBPPP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a typical example of how powerless White can be when the centre has been opened and Black has been allowed to demonstrate his attacking skills. }
1... Rf8 { Starting with the rook on the f-file... } 2. Rde1 Ne4
{ Now the knight } 3. Qe3 Qg6
{ And the queen. Everyone joins in the effort and White still can't manage to contain Black's initiative. Look at the rooks ! }
4. Kh1 R8f5 5. h3 Qf7 6. Rg1 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Rxf3 8. gxf3 Rxf3 9. Rxg7+ Kxg7 10.
Rg1+ Kf8 11. Qh6+ Ke8 { No more checks, so White has to let go. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Lupulescu, Constantin vs. Giri, Anish"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/p2nq1pp/bppbpn2/3p1p2/2PP1B2/1P1N2P1/P1QNPPBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ If the Black light-squared bishop is on the queenside, the lever he should play for will be c5 and he may not stop there... }
1... Rac8 2. a4
{ 13.cxd5  Bxf4  14.Nxf4  cxd5  15.Qb2  g5  16.Nd3  Bxd3  17.exd3  f4  followed by g4, is not exactly what White should be aiming for...   13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.cxd5  cxd5 !  A concrete decision, based on the fact that Black will take the c-file over.  15.Qb2  Bxd3  16.exd3  Rc6  17.Rac1  Rfc8 }
2... c5 3. a5 b5 { Black is already better... } 4. b4
{ None of the captures are any good for White- } 4... Bxf4 5. gxf4 dxc4 6. Nxc5
Nxc5 7. dxc5 Bb7 8. Bxb7 Qxb7
{ With a tremendous position due to the weak kingside. } 9. Nf3 Nh5
{ 20...Nd5  21.Qd2  Rfd8  22.Rfd1  Qe7  with Qf6 and c3 and White's position crumbles. }
10. Qd2 Qe4 11. Ng5 Qxf4 { was still close to winning. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Dautov, Rustem vs. Hort, Vlastimil"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3rbrk1/pp2q2p/2p1p3/3nPpp1/PP6/3N2PP/2Q1PPB1/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Qc5
{ When White has opened the c-file and has prospects on the queenside, trading queens is always an excellent idea. }
1... b6 2. Qxe7 Nxe7 3. f4
{ secures e5 while nipping Black's hopes of activity in the bud. } 3... h6 4.
a5 Nd5 5. axb6 axb6 6. Rfc1 { And White is completely dominating! } 6... Rf7 7.
Kf2 Rb7 8. Ra3 Kf8 9. Rca1 Ke7 10. Bf3 Bd7 11. fxg5
{ Black already lost on the a-file and an outside passed pawn on the h-file is more than he can deal with. }
11... hxg5 12. h4 gxh4 13. gxh4 Be8 14. h5 Nc7 15. Ra7 Rdb8 16. h6 Kf8 17. Rg1
*


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Admiraal, Miguoel vs. Lagarde, Maxime"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/1p2q1pp/2p5/p1QpNp2/3P2n1/4P3/PP2BPPP/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

Qxc5
{ Here the same try is not working, mostly because White has no initiative whatsoever. }
2. Rxc5 Nxe5 3. dxe5 f4
{ The d5 pawn is now a protected passed one : Black is much better. } *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Vladimirov, Boris T vs. Smyslov, Vassily V"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1p2q2p/p1p3p1/3pP3/1P1PpR2/2Q1PbPB/P6P/5RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Qc5
{ Here it is a different story altogether : Black's f3 bishop is useless. }
1... Qg7 { 24...Qxc5  25.bxc5  Is just horrible for Black. } 2. Qd6 g5 3. Rxf8+
Qxf8 4. Qd7 Qg7 5. Qe6+ Qf7 6. Qd6
{ Black is dominated. If he goes back to f8 with his queen, instead of repeating White will give a check on e6, trade on f8 and take advantage of the pin of the f-file to go Bg4, trade bishops, surround the resulting f3 pawn, capture it and win the endgame. }
*


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Petrosian, Tigran V vs. Cardoso, Radolfo Tan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2r1k/pp1b2pp/2pq1n2/3p1p2/PP1P4/3NP1P1/2Q2PBP/R1R3K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ When Black misses his dark-squared bishop, the last thing he wants is a bind on those very squares, since the less pieces there are, the more like he is to get squeezed to death. Here comes the master squeezer ! }
1. Qc5 { A depressing endgame for Black ! } 1... Qxc5 2. Nxc5 Rc7 3. Nxd7
{ The worst bishop is worth the best knight as long as a position may open one day. Another way to look at it is that White's bishop will now feast on all those weak pawns. }
3... Rxd7 4. b5 Rc8 5. Rc2 Rdc7 6. Rac1 Kg8 7. a5 a6 8. bxa6 bxa6 9. Bf1
{ As advertised, the prelate will grow fat and opulent in this game. } 9... Ne8
10. Bxa6 Ra8 11. Rxc6 Rxa6
{ And now dies of indigestion, but that's all according to plan. } 12. Rxc7
Nxc7 13. Rxc7 Rxa5 14. h4
{ The rook endgame is easy to convert : Black plays with neither king nor dark squares. }
14... h6 15. Kg2 Ra6 16. Rd7 Ra5 17. h5 Kf8 18. Kf3 Rb5 19. Kf4 Rb2 20. f3 Rh2
21. Rxd5 *


[White "Piece Play and Trade"]
[Black "Ivkov, Borislav vs. Malagon, Alberto"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1nb1pp/2p1p3/3p1p1q/2PPn3/1PN1P1P1/PB3PBP/2RQNRK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

Qxd1 2. Rxd1 Nxc3 3. Bxc3 a5 { Black will follow up with b5 and is not worse. }
*


[White "Endgames"]
[Black "Lebedev, Sergey Fedorovich vs. Chigorin, Mikhail Ivanovich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/p1n5/k1p1p3/b1Pp1p1p/P2P1PpP/1N2P1P1/2N1K3/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this chapter we'll have a look at some examples that didn't make the cut for the test but are still very educational. With all White pawns on dark squares, you don't need to be Chigorin to guess that Black is winning here. White just doesn't have the time to stop the knight from eating g3. }
1... Ne8
{ The knight heads for f6-e4 and its final destination, the poor defenceless martyr on g3. If White tried to defend it with his king, then the knight would head to c3 and snack on the a4 pawn. Indeed in endgames one often needs two weaknesses in the opponent's camp to win, by attacking one and then the other until the enemy is overstretched, the further the better. }
2. Nc1 Nf6 3. Nd3 Ne4 4. Nce1 Nxg3+ 5. Kd1 Ne4
{ With a completely won endgame. } 6. Ne5 Kb7 7. Nd7 Bd8 8. Ng2 Be7 9. Ne5 Bf6
10. Nd3 Nc3+ 11. Kc2 Ne2 12. Nf2 Ng1 13. Nh1 Nf3 14. Ng3 Nxh4
{ I really like how the knight danced to take White's pawns one after the other. }
15. Ne1 Nf3 { This cute little trick kills off White's last hopes. } 16. Nxf3
h4
{ It's well known that a knight fears fighting a squadron of pawn but two knights ? Still looks true ! }
17. Ne1 hxg3 18. Ng2 Ka6 19. Kb3 Bd8 20. Ka3 Ba5 21. Kb3 Bd2 22. Kc2 Bb4 23.
Kb3 Ka5 24. Nh4 Bd2 25. Ng2 Bc1
{ The last maneuver. Black gives up his bishop as he knows White has no way of covering the a-pawn, the g-pawn and keep the e3 pawn defended at the same time with only two pieces. }
26. Kc2 Kxa4 27. Kxc1 Kb3 28. Kd2 Kb2 29. Ne1 a5 30. Nd3+ Kb1 31. Ke2 a4 32.
Nb4 a3 33. Nxc6 a2 34. Kf1 a1=Q 35. Kg2 Qa6 36. Ne5 Qe2+ 37. Kxg3 Qxe3+ *


[White "Endgames"]
[Black "Kozul, Zdenko vs. Lauber, Arnd"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kn4/3n2pp/3Bp3/1p1p1p2/3P1N1P/P2KPPP1/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. h5 { This e6 pawn can't be defended in time and tactics won't help here. }
1... Nb6 2. Be7 Nc6 3. Bc5 e5 4. Ne6 e4+ 5. Ke2
{ This illustrates the concrete nature of endgames but also how mobility is nothing without having been allowed proper timing. White had better not take on e4 !   49.fxe4  fxe4+  50.Ke2  Nd7  51.Nxg7  Nf6  And in spite of being a pawn up, the rigid pawn structure favors knights who may prefer slower settings. }
5... Na4
{ 49...Nd7  50.Nxg7  Nf6  51.Nxf5  This is the difference ! We need f5 to be there for the taking ! In general in superior endgames one does not want to trade pawns, especially if those are not easily defended but handily targeted  (the very definition of a weakness in my opinion)  . }
6. Nxg7
{ Again, f5 is falling and Rome with it. The rest is but a Vandal's dream }
6... Nc3+ 7. Ke1 { 51.Kf2  is also sufficient } 7... exf3 8. Kf2 Na5 9. Kxf3
Nc4 10. Nxf5 Kd7 11. g4 Ke6 12. Ng3 Nb1 13. Ne2 Nbxa3 14. Nf4+ Kf7 15. Bxa3
Nxa3 16. Nxd5 *


[White "Endgames"]
[Black "Piket, Jeroen vs. Fontaine, Robert"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1p1b3r/1Pp3k1/p1Pp2p1/P2Pp2P/2N1P1K1/8/7R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nb1
{ a5 is isolated, White needs to hurry before Black gets the time to counterattack on the kingside. }
1... Rf7 2. Nd2 gxh4+ 3. Rxh4 Kg5 4. Rh8 Rg7 5. Nb3 Rf7 6. Rg8+ Kh5 7. Nxa5
Rf3+ 8. Kg2 Bh3+
{ 55...Rxe3  is too slow:  56.Nxb7  Ra3  and now basically any knight jump, followed by advance of the b7 pawn wins, e.g.  57.Nd6  Rxa4  58.b7 }
9. Kh2 Kh4 10. Nxc6
{ Unnecessary, but a sight to behold. It also brings about a very instructive point  (see last move, no spoilers !) }
10... bxc6 11. b7 Rf2+ 12. Kh1 Rf1+ 13. Rg1 Rf8 14. a5 Bf1 15. Rxf1 Rxf1+ 16.
Kg2 Rb1 17. a6
{ Black has no way to stop the pawns. In fact, more often than not two pawns on the sixth rank are known to overpower a rook : if one is attacked, the other is pushed and would reach Nirvana if his comrade is killed in action. }
*


[White "Endgames"]
[Black "Hambleton, Aman vs. L'Ami, Erwin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r7/rp1k2pp/2p1b3/3pPp2/pR3P1P/P3P1P1/1P2B3/2R3K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ A typical dxe5 endgame where White is the only one with prospects. The game was surprisingly one-sided. }
1. Kf2
{ Club players often forget to include their king in the endgame, but player of Ambleton's caliber is not your average club player. With Kf2 he brings the king closer to the action and improve his position. You will see later in the game how this king took a very active role in the game. }
1... Kc7 2. Rd4 Ra5
{ You might expect Black to try playing some c5-d4 but he just won't be allowed to and simply going c5 leaves d5 forever weak while White still has a free hand on the kingside. }
3. h5 b6 4. Rd2 Rc5 5. Rg1
{ And here comes the reason why this is an unplayable structure. } 5... Rf8 6.
g4 Rf7 7. Bd3 fxg4 8. Bxh7 Rf8 9. Kg3 Rb5 10. f5 Rb3 11. fxe6
{ And White is completely winning. } 11... Rxe3+ 12. Kh4 Rxe5 13. Rxg4 Rxe6 14.
Rxg7+ Kd6 15. Rg6 *


[White "Endgames"]
[Black "Beliavsky, Alexander G vs. Jussupow, Artur"]
[Result "*"]
