1... Kf6 { 40...a5 !  Before White can prevent it and grab space with b4-b5. }
2. Rh4 Rg7 3. b4
{ Now the opportunity to stop White's expansion of the queenside has gone. As mentioned before, the one weakness Black had on h7 would not be sufficient but through playing on both wings and the centre, White stretches him thinner and thinner until he breaks. }
3... Kg5 4. Rh1 Kf6 5. Rh2 Rg5 6. a4 Rg7 7. a5 Rc7 8. Rh6+ Bg6 9. Rh1 Bf5 10.
Rc1 a6 11. Rh1 Rg7 12. Rh2 Rc7 13. Rh6+ Bg6 14. Rh4 Bf5 15. e4 dxe4 16. fxe4
Bg6 17. Rf4+ Ke6
{ Black is already lost here and it's hard to pinpoint the moment of his demise since the last opportunity : a good lesson here that defence is more often than not very concrete  (calculate at every move to alter the position !)  and pressing is more gradual  (giving the opponent opportunities to go astray)  in endgames and technical positions in general. }
18. Ke3 Rg7 19. Nd3 Kd6 20. Nc5 { And White can milk this forever. } 20... Re7
21. Rf8 Kc7 22. e5 Re8 23. Rxe8 Bxe8 24. Kf4 { And White went on to win. }
24... b6 25. Na4 bxa5 26. bxa5 Bf7 27. Nc5 Bc4 28. Kg5 Be2 29. Kh6 Kd8 30. Kxh7
