4. Qg2 gxh2+ 5. Qxh2 Bb5
{ A very annoying inclusion of the bishop. Note how Black utilizes the entire board to create threats. }
6. Rfe1 Nb4
{ The knight is coming on d3 and everyone who is familiar with the 16th game of the Kasparov - Karpov 1985 match knows why this knight is called an 'octopus'. }
7. Rd6
{ But this doesn't help White at all.   26.Bf1  Preventing the knight from coming to d3 was the only move. Black can transition to a good endgame after  26...Qxh2+  27.Kxh2  Bxf1  28.Rxf1  Rad8  where he has a better minor piece and an extra pawn, but White can still resist. }
7... Nd3 { Now, however, it is all over. The rook on e1 is in huge trouble. }
8. Rf1 { 27.Bd2  Nxe1   27.Rd1  Qxd1+ } 8... Nxe5 9. fxe5 Bxf1 10. Bg2
{ 29.Bxf1  Rxf1+  wins for Black } 10... Qxh2+ 11. Kxh2 Rf2 12. Kg1 Rxg2+ 13.
Kxf1 Rc2 14. Bd2 Rxb2 15. Ke2 Kg8
