[Black "Richter, Emil vs. Opocensky, Karel"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p2n2pp/1pp1pb2/3p4/2PPp3/1Q2B1P1/PP1NPPBP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. cxd5
{ This required pretty excellent calculation. When Black is underdeveloped like this, he should always be anticipating those kinds of immediate assault. }
1... cxd5
{ 14...exd5  15.Nxe4  wins a pawn thanks to the pin on the b3-g8 diagonal. } 2.
Nxe4 dxe4 3. Bxe4 Rb8 4. Qxe6+ Kh8 5. Qh3 g6 6. Bxg6 Qe7 7. Bf5
{ Four pawns are way too many for a single piece ! } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Simagin, Vladimir Pavlovich vs. Chistiakov, Alexander Nikolaevi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b1q2k/1p4rp/2p1pQ2/4Pp2/2r3P1/2B2PK1/P7/3R1R2 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... f4+
{ The game went   31...Bd7  32.Bd2  Kg8  33.Bh6 !  This is why f4 was necessary.  Rg6  34.Rxd7  Rxf6  35.Rg7+  Kh8  36.exf6  Qb8+  37.f4  Rc3+  38.Kh4  f7 and Rg8 is coming, getting the queen for a rook.  Qf8  39.Rxh7+  Kxh7  40.Bxf8  Kg8  41.Be7  fxg4  42.Rg1  Rh3+  43.Kxg4 }
2. Kf2 Bd7 { Black is just fine as he parried White's only dangerous threats. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Vidmar, Milan Sr vs. Tartakower, Saviely"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r2qr1k/4b2p/b1p1p3/ppPpPppn/8/PQNNP1P1/1P3PBP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ne2
{ Black's next would have been f4 or b4. As mentioned in the Taking on e5 chapter, White's prospects in those structures are favourable long term, so basic prophylaxis should be emphasized all the more: if you don't die now, the other guy will later! The computer argues this is almost equal but in my experience fighting against space and the natural course of play is harder for most players. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Szabo, Laszlo vs. Steiner, Herman"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1n2pp/2p5/4pp2/1PRP4/5NP1/P2QPPBP/5RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. dxe5
{ Starting now White goes for a minority attack on the queenside, using the long range of his g2 bishop. }
1... Nxe5 2. Rd4 Qe7 3. Nxe5 Qxe5 4. a4 Be6 5. a5 a6 6. e3
{ White is in full control as Black can't move on the queenside and is dominated on the d-file. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Najdorf, Miguel vs. Grob, Henry"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/p5p1/2p1p2p/1p1n1p2/2pPP2P/2N3PN/PP2QPB1/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... fxe4
{ The d5-knight is the key to Black's central aspirations.   15...Nxc3  was the game, which shows how badly the remaining Black pieces fair  16.bxc3  a5  17.Nf4  Kh7  18.Rfe1  Ra7  19.h5  Qc7  20.exf5  exf5  21.d5  Rd8  22.Rad1  c5  23.d6  Rxd6  24.Bd5  Qd8  25.Qe8  Be6  26.Rxe6 }
2. Qxe4 Na6
{ Black will follow up with Nac7 and e5, activating all his pieces. Grabbing on c4 is closer to a Slav than a Stonewall Dutch but often the openings actually happen to transpose. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Keres, Paul vs. Panov, Vasily N"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2br2k1/ppq1b1pp/2p1p3/4Pp2/Q1PB4/4P1P1/P4PBP/3R2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. c5 { Black is cramped as the liberating c5-Bd7-Bc6 is no longer possible. }
1... a6 2. Rb1 Rf8 3. f4 Qd7 4. Qc4
{ At this point Black should at least create some counterplay through g5. }
4... Rd8 5. h4
{ White can slowly improve the position, prepare e4, g4 or the invasion of the d-file. The blockade on the dark squares denies Black any counterplay. He is playing on his first two ranks. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Mikenas, Vladas Ivanovich vs. Ragozin, Viacheslav"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3qb1k1/1p4pp/r4r2/3p1p2/1b6/pP2PPP1/P1QN2BP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f4 Rad6 2. Nf3 Qb6 3. Nd4
{ Blockade of d5 and preventing Rc6 make the Nd4 the best piece on the board. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Vidmar, Milan Jr vs. Steiner, Herman"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b4r/1p2bkp1/2p1p3/2P1Pq2/rPQ1p1pp/4P3/1B1R3P/3R1B1K w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Qc2
{ Black loses at least a rook, since White attacks the a4 rook and threatens to pin the queen with Rf2 at the same time. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Averbakh, Yuri L vs. Chistiakov, Alexander Nikolaevi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r5k1/1ppbq1pp/2n1pr2/p2p1p2/2PPn3/PP1BPN2/1BQ2PPP/2R1K2R w K - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. g3
{ A key move. White will redirect his bishop to f1-g2 with an edge. Without a Black dark squared bishop this makes all the more sense, pawns on the kingside are all the safer. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Kotov, Alexander vs. Bhend, Edwin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2r1k/1p4pp/p1nqpn2/2b2p2/2B2N2/4PP2/PPQBN1PP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... e5 { There is no reason to fear White's discoveries. } 2. Nd3
{ 16.Bc1  Qe7  17.Nd5  Nxd5  18.Bxd5  Nb4  19.Qc3  Bd7  is much better for Black. He has more space and superior pieces. }
2... Ba7 3. Kh1 Bd7
{ Black has space and activity, but no clear target, so he's only slightly better. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Geller, Efim P vs. Mueller, Paul"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1nb1pp/2p1pn2/3p1p2/2PP4/3N2P1/PPQ1PPBP/RNB2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxc4
{ If Black does not challenge White's centre, he will suffer as the Nd3 is in a perfect position. }
2. Qxc4 Nb6 3. Qc3 Ne4 { Else White will put a pawn on that square after Nd2. }
4. Bxe4 fxe4 5. Ne5 Nd5 6. Qc2 c5
{ Now Black has comfortably equalized, for instance is White chases material with }
7. dxc5 Qc7 8. Nc4 Qxc5 9. Qxe4 Nf6 10. Qc2 Qh5
{ White is in terrible shape on the light squares and did not even start to develop his queenside. His prospects are very bleak. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Unzicker, Wolfgang vs. Uhlmann, Wolfgang"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p2n2pp/1pp1pn2/3p1p2/2PP4/NP3NP1/P3PPBP/R1Q2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. cxd5 { Simple tactics. } 1... cxd5 { 11....exd5  12.Qxc6 } 2. Qc6
{ Double attack on a8 and e6. The game could end this way: } 2... Ba6 3. Qxe6+
Kh8 4. Ng5 Qe8 5. Qxf5 Qe7 6. Nc2 Ne4
{ 16...Bxe2  17.Rfe1  is, of course, better than allowing checkmate, but the position is still hopeless. }
7. Qxh7# *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Tal, Mihail vs. Solmanis, Zigfrids"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb3k1/pp2q1p1/2p1pr1p/3pNp2/2PPn3/2N1P3/PPQ2PPP/2R1KB1R w K - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. cxd5 Nxc3 { 12...exd5  13.Nxd5  cxd5  14.Qxc8+  wins a pawn. } 2. d6 Qxd6 3.
Qxc3 { Simple tactics have given White a big structural edge. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Pachman, Ludek vs. De Greif, Boris"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3q1k1/1bp2rpp/p3p3/2p1Pp2/2P1p3/1P2P3/P1Q1NPPP/2RR2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Qb2
{ Next is Qa3, targeting c5, forcing the Black queen to defend it. Then White will invade the d-file unchallenged. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Tipary, Lajos vs. Szabo, Laszlo"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/pp1q1npp/2b1p3/3pPpb1/1B1P1NP1/1Q1BP2P/PP6/2R2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Ba4
{ 19...fxg4  20.Qc2 !  would be dramatic, as Black has very few pieces to oppose White on the light squares, the black bishop being stuck on the other side of the board. }
2. Qc3 fxg4 3. hxg4 Bb5 4. Kg2 Bxd3 5. Qxd3 Be7 6. Rh1 Ng5 7. Rh5 Ne4
{ Trading light-squared bishops was key for Black to claim equality and probably even more, as White's attack on the kingside may not be enough to balance chances. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Szabo, Laszlo vs. Rethy, Pal"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1rbq1rk1/p1n1b3/2p1pn1p/1p1p1pp1/2PP4/PP3PPN/1BQNP1BP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... bxc4
{ If White is allowed to close down the queenside with c5 he will be able to burst through the centre with e4. }
2. bxc4 Ba6 { Next is dc4 and c5 : Black has adequate chances, for instance }
3. e4 dxc4 4. Nf2 { 19.Bc3  Nb5  wins the d4 pawn } 4... c3
{ 19....Nb5  is now met with the simple  20.Qxc4 } 5. Bxc3 Nb5
{ Black is even better in this version. He could also have picked up an exchange on the previous move. Either is fine. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Mukhitdinov, Mamadzhan vs. Chistiakov, Alexander Nikolaevi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r5k1/pp1b1rbp/3Bn3/2PRP2q/1P2Q1p1/4P1P1/P4PBP/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rd4 { Bc6 was Black's next against anything else. } 1... Nxd4 2. exd4 *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Sherwin, James T vs. Mednis, Edmar John"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4nk1/ppbbq1pp/2p1p3/2Pp1p1P/3P1P2/1P1BPN2/P5Q1/2K1B1R1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

h6
{ The only way White is going anywhere on the kingside is by weakening the dark squares, which is also the h5 pawn only chance to survive in the long run. Now Black is just much better. }
2. Bh4 Qf7 3. Ne5 Bxe5 4. fxe5 Kh8
{ Followed by b6 and crashing through the queenside. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Lengyel, Levente vs. Tipary, Lajos"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppn3pp/2pbp3/3p1p2/2PPP3/P1NB1PP1/1PQ4P/R1B1K2R b KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... fxe4
{ Black opens up the f-file so as to let his light square bishop in and prevent the White king from castling.   12...e5  13.exd5  cxd5   13...exd4  14.Ne2  14.c5  Be7  15.O-O }
2. fxe4 e5 3. exd5 exd4 4. Ne2 Bg4
{ White's king is way too weak to survive staying in the center. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Forintos, Gyozo Victor vs. Spassky, Boris Vasilievich"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rr2k1/1b4pp/1p1bp3/p1pp1p1q/2PPn3/1P2PNP1/P4PBP/BQRR2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxc4 { Always a consideration with a Bb7 ! } 2. bxc4 Nxg3
{ Look for tactics on the kingside when your queen happens to lurk over there. }
3. hxg3 Bxf3 4. Re1 Rf8 5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. Qb2 Rf6
{ Covering g7 and preparing to slide over the 6th file. } 7. Qe5 Bd6 8. Qd4
{ 27.Qxd6  Rh6  with a mate on h1 coming. } 8... Rg6 9. Rc2 Bc5 10. Qf4 Bxg2
11. Kxg2 Rh6 { Sliding completed. } 12. Qf3 Qh3+ 13. Kg1 Rd8
{ Black only had one inactive piece and White's only counterplay was on the d-file. Spassky realizes he has time to consolidate before finishing White off. }
14. Bc3 f4
{ The last opening of the White king's position is worth so much more than a pawn. }
15. exf4 Rg6 { Catastrophe is coming to g3. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Pachman, Ludek vs. Fischer, Robert James"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq2k1/2p4p/bpn1p2r/p2P1p2/3Pn1p1/PP2PN2/1BQ2PPP/2RR1BK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxa6
{ With best play White is winning but in this chaotic position both players erred. }
1... gxf3 2. gxf3 Qg5+ 3. Kf1
{ 20.Kh1  Qh5  21.Rg1+  Kh8  22.Rg2  Rg8  23.Rxg8+  Kxg8  24.Rg1+  Kf7  25.Rg2  Qxf3  26.dxc6  Rg6  27.Bf1  Rxg2  28.Bxg2  Nxf2+  29.Kg1  also wins, though it doesn't appear too obvious at the start of the line }
3... Rxh2 4. fxe4
{ 21.Bxc8 !  The cleanest.  Qh5  22.Ke2  Rxf2+  23.Kd3  Rxc2  24.Kxc2  Qxf3  25.dxc6  Nf2  26.Bxe6+  Kf8  27.Bc4  Qe4+  28.Bd3  Qxc6+  29.Kb1 }
4... Rf8 5. e5
{ White thinks that closing the e-file is most important but he loses valuable time allowing the f-pawn to advance ever forward.   22.Rd2  fxe4  23.Qxe4  exd5  24.Qxd5+  Qxd5  25.Bc4  still wins. }
5... f4 6. e4 f3 7. Ke1 exd5
{ Black is totally winning, for instance   24...Qg1+  was a huge blunder by Fischer  25.Kd2  Qxf2+  26.Kc3  Qg3  27.Qd3  And White converted his extra piece. }
8. Qxc6
{ 25.exd5  Ne7  the black knight is coming from either d5 and f5, the white king has nowhere to run. }
8... Qg1+ 9. Bf1 Qxf1+ 10. Kxf1 Rh1# *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Keres, Paul vs. Maslov, Leonid P"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rr3k/1b2b1pp/1pp1n1q1/3pPp2/1P6/1QNBPP2/1B4PP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ne2 { The main weakness on f5 is easily targeted. } 1... Rc7 2. Ng3 Rf8 3.
Nxf5 { No e6 pawn means Black is getting steamrolled on the kingside. } 3...
Bd8 4. Nd6 Qh6 5. f4
{ With an overwhelming positional and also material advantage. } 5... c5 6. Bb1
c4 7. Qc2
{ The only time a battery involves a queen in front is when checkmate is in the air. Spoilers : it's gonna happen. }
7... c3 8. Bc1 d4 9. exd4 Bd5 10. Rd3 Nxf4 11. Rxf4 Rxf4 12. Rh3
{ An exchange is more than a good investment for the collapse of h7. } 12...
Be4 13. Nxe4 Rcf7 14. Bxf4 Qxf4 15. Rf3 *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Benko, Pal C vs. Guimard, Carlos Enrique"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b3rk/pp1q1nbp/2p1p3/B1PpPpp1/3Q4/3N2P1/PP2PPBP/1R3RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

b6 { A familiar scenario by now : Black has to act before getting smothered. }
2. cxb6 axb6 3. Bxb6 Ba6 4. Nc5 Qc8 5. f4 gxf4 6. gxf4 Nd6
{ The position is now double edged. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Polugaevsky, Lev vs. Cherepkov, Alexander V"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/p5pp/1p2p3/2bb1pq1/4P3/1PBB4/P3QPPP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... fxe4 { A series of captures nets Black a pawn. } 2. Bxe4 Rxf2 3. Rxf2
Bxf2+ 4. Qxf2 { 22.Kxf2  Qh4+  23.Kg1  Qxe4 } 4... Rxc3 5. Bxd5 Qxd5
{ Black is close to winning, as taking the queen would allow massive trades after the check on c1. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Wisse, S. vs. Timman, Jan H"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/p6p/bp3b2/2np1ppq/1B1Nn3/1P2P1P1/P1Q1NPBP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. f3
{ Simple, nonetheless it's interesting how Black's position simply collapses now. }
1... Nd6 2. Bxc5
{ It is important to mentions that shenanigans such as   20...Rfc8  don't work because of a simple capture  21.Bxd6  Rxc2  22.Rxc2  and White has too much material for the queen. }
2... bxc5 3. Qxc5 Rad8 4. Rfe1
{ The Black knight is denied any active square by the f3 and b3 pawns, while White's own knights guarantee the centre will never collapse. He's also a pawn up, which means his position is winning. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Lengyel, Levente vs. Farago, Ivan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/p4kpp/2n1p3/1B1p1p2/3P1P2/bP2P1P1/2nB3P/2N3K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... N6xd4 2. exd4 Nxd4
{ Black wants to take on b5 or fork the other bishop through f3, and } 3. Be2
Bxc1 { won't help. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Radulov, Ivan vs. Farago, Ivan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r1rk1/pp2b1pp/4p3/2pP1p2/b1P5/4PB2/PB3PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... exd5 2. Bxd5+ Rxd5 3. cxd5 Rd8 4. Rfe1 Bc2
{ Preventing e4. Now the queenside pawns give full compensation for the invested exchange as d5 is falling. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Happel, Henk vs. Farago, Ivan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3qrk1/p2nb1pp/b1p1pn2/3p1p2/2PP4/3N1PP1/P1QNP1BP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... c5
{ White spent too much time getting a knight on d3. Again a regular pattern. }
2. Qa4
{ 14.cxd5  Opening your house door while your shirt is unbuttoned is not a recipe for success.  Nxd5  15.dxc5  Bxd3  16.Qxd3  Nxc5  17.Qa3  Ne4  18.Qd3  Bc5+  19.Kh1  Nxg3+  Kaboom!  20.hxg3  Qh5+  21.Bh3  Qxh3# }
2... Qc8 3. Ba3 dxc4 4. Nxc4 Nb6 5. Nxb6 axb6
{ Black is winning some material after   18.Ne5  Bxe2  19.Qb3  Bxf1 } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Platonov, Igor V vs. Kholmov, Ratmir D"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4r1k1/pq2r1pp/1ppb1n2/3p1p2/3Pn3/1P1QPN2/PBR1NPPP/5RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. h3
{ prevents Ng4. Now Black needs to foment an attack on the kingside, but it looks insufficient, such as }
1... Nd7 { 20...Nh5  21.Ne5  c5  22.Nf4 } 2. Rfc1 Re6 3. Qd1 a5 4. Ne5
{ Mass trades on e5 would drop the c6 pawn, so Black in dispair traded once but ultimately the c-pawn dropped anyway. }
4... Nxe5 5. dxe5 Bc5 6. Qd3 Qf7 7. a3 h6 8. Nf4 Rxe5 { Desperation. } 9. Bxe5
Rxe5 10. b4 { And the c-pawn will fall. White has a decisive advantage. } 10...
axb4 11. axb4 Nxf2 12. Rxf2 Bxe3 13. Rxc6
{ White is a rook up, which will only be a knight once the trade on f2 is done. Still good enough to claim the full point. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Johansson, Gunnar1 vs. Olafsson, Fridrik"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/p3q2p/1p2pb2/3pNpp1/PPnP4/3N1PP1/Q4P1P/1R1R2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Bxe5
{ With no light pieces, Black can start targeting White's structural defects. Of course, the main point is to secure a central protected passed pawn. }
2. dxe5 f4
{ Next is Qf7 targeting f3. White in turn does... nothing. The e5 pawn is also vulnerable as White can't protect it by putting his own pawn on f4. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Adamski, Jan vs. Csom, Istvan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r1rk1/pb1qb1pp/1pp1p3/3pPp2/2PN4/1P1QP3/PB3PPP/2RR2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. cxd5
{ It's really important to prevent c5. So Black tries to keep his options open with   17.Qc2  c5 }
1... exd5 2. e6 Qd6 3. b4 f4
{ White has the easiest position, although the computer might be able to defend this. An example of human interaction would be }
4. exf4 Qxf4 5. Qe2 Rc8 6. Rc3 c5 7. Rf3 Qc7 8. Nb5 Qd8 9. Rg3
{ And White has better prospects, although the position is still fairly complicated. }
9... d4 10. bxc5 bxc5 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Rxg7+ Kxg7 13. Rxd4 Qxd4 14. Bxd4+ Bf6
15. Qg4+ Kh8 16. h4 { Where White is winning with his 100 pawns. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Ree, Hans vs. Ivkov, Borislav"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/3nb1pp/ppp1pn2/2Pp1p2/1P1P1P2/P1NBP1N1/3B2PP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... a5 2. O-O Ba6
{ We already talked about trading the light-squared bishops. Now Black is clearly better. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Lputian, Smbat G vs. Akopian, Gagik"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qrk1/pp1n2pp/2pbp3/3nNp2/3P4/1PN3P1/P1Q1PPBP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxc6
{ As much as saying there should be a pawn on d5 instead of a knight, I'd like to emphasize the importance of 2-3 move tactics, which represent the overwhelming majority of arguments in a strategic debate. }
1... bxc6 2. Nxd5 cxd5 3. Qc6
{ White is getting his piece back after investing a pawn. The fact that it's the dark-squared bishop, Black's usual best light lieutenant does not help. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Kasparov, Garry vs. Jussupow, Artur"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r2k1/2p1b1pp/1p2p1q1/4P3/2Q1pP2/P3P3/1B3RPP/6K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Bh4
{ Yusupov actually lost this game but he had an amazing opportunity punctuated by this attack on the future King's king. }
2. g3 Bxg3 3. hxg3 Qxg3+ 4. Kf1 { 27.Rg2  Rd1+  is no better } 4... Rd1+ 5. Ke2
Qg4+ 6. Rf3 Qxf3#
{ Not a very difficult forced line. As an aside, I would recommend doing some AntiChess  (also called losing chess)  exercises to work on your concrete calculation. You're welcome ! }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Kraidman, Yair vs. Murey, Jacob"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b2rk1/1pp1q1pp/r1n5/p2p1p2/3Pn3/1N3NP1/PP2PPBP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nc5
{ The start of a great regrouping to secure White's dominance over the queenside. }
1... Rb6
{ 14...Nxc5  15.Rxc5  is precisely what White wants - eliminate the strong knight on e4. }
2. Na4 Ra6 3. Qb3 Qf7 4. e3
{ Black can't move at all, he is much, much worse. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Psakhis, Lev vs. Noskov, Anatolij"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1q1k1/pp1n1rpp/2p2b2/2Pppp2/1P1P4/3N1PP1/PBQ1P1BP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. e4
{ We previously saw that with a Nd3 and f3 played, Black needs to play on the queenside fast. This is what happens when he doesn't. }
1... fxe4 2. fxe4 dxe4 3. Nxe5 Nxe5 4. dxe5 Bxe5
{ Black reacted in the most natural way, taking everything coming to smack him, but he's the one getting whacked. }
5. Rxf7 Kxf7 6. Rf1+ Bf6
{ 23...Kg8  24.Qxe4  is just losing due to the pin on the e-file } 7. Qe2
{ The Black king is getting caught after a trade on f6 followed by Qh5. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Velikov, Petar vs. Kuzmin, Gennadi P"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1p1r1kpp/1qpBp3/p3Pp2/P1Q1n1P1/1P2P3/5P1P/3R2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Qd8 { Redirecting from queenside to kingside. } 2. Qd4
{ This is a losing move.   26.gxf5  is strongly met with  26...Qg5+  27.Kf1  Qxf5  when Black is winning  It was probably most resilient to give up a pawn with   26.f3  Nxd6  27.Rxd6  Rxd6  28.exd6  Qxd6  with some drawing chances in the ensuing queen endgame }
2... Qh4
{ The poor Bd6 looks great but is totally useless to defend his king. } 3. gxf5
{ Defending the f2 pawn doesn't help:   27.Rf1  Qxg4+  28.Kh1  Qh3  29.Kg1  and now the simplest is  29...Ng5  with the threat of Nf3, winning on the spot, basically. }
3... Qxf2+ { Now everything falls with check. } 4. Kh1 Qf3+
{ The rest doesn't require particular commentary. } 5. Kg1 Qg4+ 6. Kf1 Qxf5+ 7.
Ke2 Qg4+ 8. Ke1 Qg1+ 9. Ke2 Qxh2+
{ Now Black can choose between losing a piece after   34.Kd3  Nxd6  and getting mated on any other square. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Pinter, Jozsef vs. Larsen, Bent"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4nk1/2qb2rp/2p1p3/1pPpPpB1/p2Q1P2/P5P1/1P2P1B1/R2R2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bh4
{ Black was going to sac an exchange on g5 and weaken e5, muddying the waters. Now White can calmly improve his superior position. }
1... Be8 2. Bf3 Nd7 3. Kf2 Bg6 4. Rh1 Kf7 5. Bg5
{ And White is in total control and went on to win quickly by arranging a quick g4 break. }
5... Qa5
{ Notice how Black has no way to defend his kingside, instead moving his queen to and fro. The a8 rook won't even bother. }
6. g4
{ The preapartion has been done and now White can finally open the position up! }
6... Kg8
{ 30...fxg4  31.Bxe4  would open up the position in White's favour. He could next go about preparing a timely e4 break and there is little Black could do to avoid being suffocated. }
7. Bf6 Rf7 8. gxf5 exf5 9. Bh5 { Great, energetic play! } 9... Nxf6 10. exf6
Qd8 11. Bxg6 hxg6 12. Rag1 Rxf6 13. Rxg6+ Rxg6 14. Qh8+
{ And Whtie checkmates in several moves. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Hamed, Ahmed vs. Short, Nigel D"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5r1k/6qp/4b1pN/1R1p2Q1/p2P4/4P1P1/1P5P/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. g4
{ Prevents Bh3 and mate on f1 for good. Now come Black's futile attempts to generate threats   34.Kg2  Qc7  35.Rc5  Qd6  36.Rc6  taking on c6 would allow mate on e5, but...  36...Bh3+!!  37.Kxh3  Qxc6  38.Qe5+  Qf6 }
1... Qc7 2. Rc5 Qb8
{ 35...Qd6  36.Rc6  No intermediate check on h3 here! This illustrates why preventing an idea altogether should be looked at before limiting its consequences. }
3. Qe7
{ Now he has to offer the trade of queens before the sun sets on the seventh rank. }
3... Qe8 4. Rc7 Qxe7 5. Rxe7 Bc8 6. h4
{ White is a pawn up, Black pieces can't move. This is an easy win. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Timman, Jan H vs. Short, Nigel D"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r4r1/1p3b2/2pk1n1p/P2p1p2/1R1P1P2/2N1P2P/2R2K2/5B2 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This shows all that White is hoping for against the Stonewall. } 1. Rcb2 Kc7
2. Bd3 Be6 3. Na4 Nd7 4. Nc5 Nxc5 5. dxc5
{ White will improve his position on both sides, prepare an invasion through d4-e5 with his king. Black is powerless as he has no lever to change the narrative. }
*


