[SetUp "1"]

1... cxd4 { White tried for too much, too fast... } 2. exd4
{ 18.Nc6  Qd7  19.Nxd4  c5  picks up the knight. } 2... c5
{ d4 is a classic target when White is underdeveloped. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Ardiansyah, Haji vs. Portisch, Lajos"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1qrk1/p2b2pp/3bpn2/1p1p4/3PP3/P1NQ1BP1/1P3B1P/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... b4 2. axb4 Bxb4 3. Rfe1 dxe4
{ Only now that White can't take it with the knight due to the pin. } 4. Bxe4
Nxe4 5. Rxe4 a5
{ White is collapsing after a4-a3, not to mention the incredible weakness of the kingside light squares. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Vaganian, Rafael A vs. Ljubojevic, Ljubomir"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/Rprq2bk/4p3/2Pp1p2/1N1PnPp1/3Q2PP/6K1/4B3 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... gxh3+
{ This game shows quite well how crucial it is to have the light squared bishop if you are White. }
2. Kxh3 Kg6 3. Kg2 Bf6 4. Bf2
{ And now extra kudos for finding the following Black maneuver along the h-file. }
4... Qe8
{ The star concept of bringing everyone to the kingside while the White rook and knight strut and fret their hour upon the queenside until they are no more. }
5. Bg1 Rh7 6. c6 Qh8 7. cxb7 Rh1
{ Qh3 is coming to pick up the homeless White king. } 8. g4
{ A move like   53.Ra8  loses after  53...Qh3+  54.Kf3  Qxg3+  55.Ke2  Qg2+  56.Kd1  Rxg1+  57.Qf1  Rxf1# }
8... Bxd4 9. gxf5+ Kxf5 { The king is surprisingly save here. } 10. Ra1
{ 55.Bxd4  of course, loses after  55....Qh2+  56.Kf3  Qg3+  57.Ke2  Re1# }
10... Bxg1
{ Qh2 is coming anyway so White stops the bleeding by blowing his head off. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Kozul, Zdenko vs. Jussupow, Artur"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1r3k1/3nq1pp/bpp1p3/3p1p2/1bPPn3/1P1Q1NP1/1B1NPPBP/R1R3K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rxa6 Rxa6 2. cxd5 Ra2 3. Rxc6
{ White has two pawns for the exchange but this is far from the end of the story. You had to see what follows. }
3... Rca8 { 18...Rxc6  19.dxc6  Rxb2  loses to  20.c7 } 4. dxe6 Ndf6
{ 19...Rxb2  20.exd7  Qxd7  21.Qc4+  Kh8  22.Nf1  is better for White } 5. Nxe4
fxe4 6. Qb1 exf3 7. Bxf3
{ Another case of four pawns against a rook. White has three passers in the centre that cannot be stopped. The fact that he has an unchallenged light-squared bishop is a very significant help. In practice he is a huge favourite, though the computer might pull a miracle. }
