[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar vs. Pelletier, Yannick"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn3rk1/3nq1pp/b1pbp3/p2pNp2/N1PP4/4Q1P1/PB2PPBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Bxe5 2. dxe5 Qb4
{ We have already seen this game in Taking on e5 chapter. Let's continue for a couple of more moves. }
3. cxd5 cxd5
{ 16...Qxa4  17.dxe6  is losing for Black, because the knight on d7 is trapped. }
4. Qb3 Bc4 5. Qc2 { 18.Qxb4  axb4  and now the knight on a4 is trapped. } 5...
Nc6
{ Black is walking over White's whole position but there is only one target on e5 which is easily defended by f4. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Kamsky, Gata vs. Lou, Yiping"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pb1n3p/1p1p4/3p4/3Pnp2/1PN2NP1/PQ3PBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Ne2
{ Black has to attack on the kingside, so we simply bring an extra defender there, claiming the very square Black was aiming for in the process. }
1... Ba6 2. Nxf4 Rxf4
{ 17...Bxf1  18.Rxf1  With overwhelming compensation as the light squares are extremely weak all over Black's camp. }
3. gxf4 Bxf1 4. Rxf1
{ And despite the ugly pawn structure, White is doing fine, as Black's pawn structure is equally bad and his king is rather exposed. }
4... Qf6 5. Qc1 Kh8 6. Qc6 Rd8 7. Ng5
{ Very powerful move.   22.Qxd5  Qxf4  is unclear. } 7... Nxg5 8. fxg5 Qxg5 9.
Qxd5
{ White is a pawn up for very little. Black's chances of survival are slim. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Meskovs, Nikita vs. Socko, Bartosz"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4nk1/1bp3r1/pp1b2q1/3p2P1/3Pp1QB/2N1P1N1/PP4P1/2RR2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Rh7 { Next is Bc8, ousting the queen before snacking on the h4 bishop. }
2. Rf1
{ White can't save material, e.g.   24.Nh1  Bc8  25.Qe2  Rxh4  the bishop is also hanging. }
2... Bc8 3. Nf5 { A desperate tactical try that also fails horribly. } 3... Rf7
4. Nh6+ Qxh6 5. gxh6+ Bxg4 { Black has won a piece. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Nisipeanu, Liviu Dieter vs. Potapov, Alexander1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/1ppb2pp/2nb1n2/pB1p1p2/3P1B2/P3PN2/1P1N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Should Black take on f4 ? } 1... Bxf4
{ Here it's a big mistake as Black gets no target in exchange for conceding the e5 square.   11...O-O  or immediately h6-g5, though inferior for Black, still gave him chances for a decent fight. }
2. exf4 O-O 3. Rc1 Ne7 4. Bd3 a4 5. Ne5 Ne4 6. Qc2 c6 7. Rfe1 Be8 8. f3
{ The point! White can always evict the enemy knight with f3, while Black is unable to do the same. White has an advantage. }
8... Qb6
{ Interesting idea but White can give back the piece right after taking it. }
9. fxe4 Qxd4+ 10. Kh1 fxe4
{ Interesting idea but White can give back the piece right after taking it. }
11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 Ng6 13. Rcd1 Qb6 14. Qc4+ Bf7 15. Nxf7 Rxf7 16. Rd7 Qb3
17. Bd3 b5 18. Qxc6 Raf8 19. Rxf7 Qxf7 20. Bxb5 Qxf4 21. Qc4+ Qxc4 22. Bxc4+
Kh8 23. Bb5 h5 24. Re8 Rxe8 25. Bxe8 Ne5 26. Bxa4 Nc4 27. Bb5 Nxb2 28. a4 Nd1
29. a5 Nc3 30. Bc6 *


