[Black "Liu, Yan vs. Bu, Xiangzhi"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/1bp3pp/pp2p3/2bpPp2/2P1n3/1PNBP3/PB2QPPP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Na4 { The knight has no future, so by all means let's trade it ! } 1... f4
{ 14...Be7  15.cxd5  exd5  16.Qc2  Rc8  17.f3  b5  18.fxe4  dxe4  19.Bc4+  bxc4  20.Rfd1  Qe8  21.Qxc4+  Kh8  22.Nc5  Bxc5  23.Qxc5  White is strategically winning with his monstrous e pawn. }
2. Bxe4 dxe4 3. exf4 Rxf4 4. Nxc5 bxc5 5. Qe3 Rf5 6. Qxc5
{ White is a pawn up and it's hard to believe that with so few light pieces left he can be assaulted on the kingside. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Cvitan, Ognjen vs. Brkic, Ante"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2r2/pb6/1ppk4/3p1pp1/1P1Pn3/4P1P1/P1R1NPB1/2R3K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Ba6
{ White is going nowhere on the c-file so Black starts active operations. The a6-f1 diagonal is extremely weak, illustrating that fianchettoing the bishop on g2 may not always be optimal against the Stonewall. }
2. f3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bd3
{ First breaking the rooks' coordination and preventing any tactics along the c-file.   30...Rfe8 ?!  31.b5 ! }
4. Rd2 Bc4 5. e4
{ Not strictly necessary, but Black was better even if White played passively. }
5... fxe4 6. fxe4 dxe4 7. Nxe4+ Nxe4
{ Attacking the d2 rook was the whole point of first going to d3. } 8. Bxe4 Bd5
{ Black can easily target White's advanced pawns. This is a very dangerous endgame for White. }
*


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Carlsen, Magnus #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1p6/2p1qnp1/2Ppbp1p/1P2P3/p4PPB/P1Q4P/3RBRK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxe4 2. fxe4 Bb2
{ White is in fact forced to go all-in now since the a2 pawn will die. In the game the great opponent was not up to the task. }
3. exf5 Qxa2 { Threatening Bd4+ and Qxc2. } 4. Bf2 g5
{ Closing the kingside : if Black is not mated, he just wins by promoting his a-pawn. }
5. Rfe1 Qf7 6. Re6 Ng4 7. Bxg4 hxg4 8. Rg6+ Kh7 9. Rd7
{ This doesn't work, but Black was better anyway. } 9... Qxd7 10. f6 Qd1+
{ The simplest, as it simplifies the situation and Black's queen is coming back on a1 very soon.   33...Rxf6  was also winning, though, but why complicate matters. }
11. Qxd1 Kxg6 12. Qd3+ Kh6 13. h4 gxh3
{ And White decided he has had enough. The a-pawn decides. } *


