[Black "Anand, Viswanathan vs. Carlsen, Magnus #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1p6/2p1qnp1/2Ppbp1p/1P2P3/p4PPB/P1Q4P/3RBRK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... dxe4 2. fxe4 Bb2
{ White is in fact forced to go all-in now since the a2 pawn will die. In the game the great opponent was not up to the task. }
3. exf5 Qxa2 { Threatening Bd4+ and Qxc2. } 4. Bf2 g5
{ Closing the kingside : if Black is not mated, he just wins by promoting his a-pawn. }
5. Rfe1 Qf7 6. Re6 Ng4 7. Bxg4 hxg4 8. Rg6+ Kh7 9. Rd7
{ This doesn't work, but Black was better anyway. } 9... Qxd7 10. f6 Qd1+
{ The simplest, as it simplifies the situation and Black's queen is coming back on a1 very soon.   33...Rxf6 }
11. Qxd1 Kxg6 12. Qd3+ Kh6 13. h4 gxh3
{ And White decided he has had enough. The a-pawn decides. } *


[White "Final Test"]
[Black "Melkumyan, Hrant vs. Gunnarsson, Jon Viktor"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pb4pp/1ppqpn2/8/2pPpN1P/2R1P1P1/PPQ2PB1/5RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... b5
{ The key to those positions is to understand that c4 is a much, much more valuable pawn than e4 because White is not going to create any kind of initiative with his d-e pawns, while the four against two on the queenside will provide opportunities for counterplay.   16...e5  17.dxe5  Qxe5  18.Rxc4  Ba6  19.Rxe4  Nxe4  20.Bxe4  Bxf1  21.Bxh7+  Kf7  22.Kxf1  White is much better despite being down two exchanges. Why ? Simple. His light pieces are stronger than Black's rooks.  Qf6  23.Bf5  Rfd8  24.Be6+  Ke7  25.Qxc6  Rd1+  26.Kg2  Rad8  27.e4  Qc7 and e5 is coming. }
2. Bxe4 Rae8 { either e5 or Nd5 next gives Black adequate counterplay. } *


