[Black "Vallejo Pons, Francisco vs. Romero Holmes, Alfonso"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/np2bbpp/2p5/1P1p1p2/3P4/1QB3P1/4PPBP/R3NRK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. bxc6 bxc6 2. Qb7
{ Black can't keep the knight on a7 so c6 falls right away. } 2... Nb5 3. Qxc6
{ Just a pawn up, simple as that. } 3... Na3 4. Bb2 Rc8 5. Qa6 Nc4 6. Nd3 Ra8
{ This actually helps White, who wants nothing more than trading all the heavy pieces to convert his extra pawn. The defending side in a static position would rather trade pawns than pieces in general to foment counterplay. The only exception is the erection of fortresses. }
7. Qxa8 Qxa8 8. Rxa8 Rxa8 9. Ra1 Rxa1+ 10. Bxa1 Bd6 11. Bc3 Kf8 12. e3 Ke7 13.
Kf1 Ke6 14. Ke1 g5 15. h3 Bg6 16. Nc5+ Bxc5 17. dxc5
