[White "A Stonewall Concise Repertoire"]
[Black "Stonewall 7-b3"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter, I'll provide a simple coverage of both sides' plans and move orders. Don't expect flashing novelties, brand new concepts or any such adventure. The Stonewall is in itself already very entertaining and Black stands fine in the Main Lines as far as I can see, and certainly up to my level. I guarantee however that after looking as the few lines in this chapter you'll be perfectly equipped for entering a decent middlegame, for which the rest of the book prepares you. Let's go ! }
1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6
{ The most flexible move, developing a knight to a useful square and still hiding which Dutch setup will Black embark on. }
3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 c6 5. Nf3 d5 6. O-O Bd6
{ More active than   6...Be7  as Black is fighting for the e5 square. } 7. b3
{ We'll start by White's main plan of going either Ba3 to trade Black's good bishop on d6 or Bb2 to control Black's main weak square on e5. As Petrosian used to say though, it is only one square ! }
7... Qe7
{ Black also has the option of castling right away but I would rather have White waste a few tempi to play Ba3 : besides the queen belongs on e7 anyway. }
8. a4
{ This is one way of forcing Ba3, but White gives up control over the b4 square. }
8... a5 9. Ba3 Bxa3 10. Nxa3 O-O 11. Nc2
{ A typical manoeuvre of which we'll see more examples in the later parts of the book. }
11... b6 12. Nce1 Na6 13. Nd3 Bb7
{ Compared to the typical Black construction in this line, White has already committed to a4, which means that a well timed c5 followed by capturing with the b-pawn will expose White's b3 pawn. I don't believe Black has any issues here. }
*


