{ You would imagine that having gone 4... c6, I would call for 5... d6  (which I in fact used once to win a good game in the Paris Championship)  , but White has ways to force us to go d5 anyway in other move orders, so rather than go into the woods and lose you while climbing trees, I prefer to allow for a simple plan and know the one different idea that White has in those positions. }
6. O-O Bd6 7. Bf4 Be7
{ I know, I know. Why did we go Bd6-e7 ? Because White was planning Nf4, after which preparing e5 is optimal. Now that the option is gone, we don't trade bishops and prepare to chase the Bf4. }
8. Nd2 O-O 9. Qc2 h6 10. Bxb8 { Else we go g5 and isolate the Nh3. } 10... Rxb8
11. Nf4 Bd6 12. Nd3 Bd7 13. Nf3 Be8 14. e3 Bh5
{ With no White dark-squared bishop, it's time to assault the kingside through f4. A kingside attack in this structure is most often successful without that White bishop, even better when we have our own dark-squared bishop. }
*


[White "A Stonewall Concise Repertoire"]
[Black "Rare Lines Stonewall"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 c6 5. Nh3 d5
{ You would imagine that having gone 4... c6, I would call for 5... d6  (which I in fact used once to win a good game in the Paris Championship)  , but White has ways to force us to go d5 anyway in other move orders, so rather than go into the woods and lose you while climbing trees, I prefer to allow for a simple plan and know the one different idea that White has in those positions. }
6. O-O Bd6 7. Bf4 Be7
{ I know, I know. Why did we go Bd6-e7 ? Because White was planning Nf4, after which preparing e5 is optimal. Now that the option is gone, we don't trade bishops and prepare to chase the Bf4. }
8. Nd2 O-O 9. Qc2 h6 10. Bxb8 { Else we go g5 and isolate the Nh3. } 10... Rxb8
11. Nf4 Bd6 12. Ng6 Re8 13. Nf3 Ne4
{ The knight on g6 is not stable but Black has one issue, as usual for this structure : the e5-square. Hence Black wants to go Nd6-f7 and Qf6 to patrol there as much as possible. }
