[White "A Stonewall Concise Repertoire"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ To finish this theoretical part, let's have a look at the lines where White does not go g3 right away or not at all. I'll be honest about it : you won't only see pure Stonewall structures here, as they work better for Black with a White bishop on g2. }
2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 d5
{ As long as the dark-squared bishop won't go to f4 controlling e5, this is the way to go. Why ? Because, believe it or not, the White light-square bishop stands better on d3 than g2 is his dark-squared brother gets to occupy the centre, as one bishop attacks the squares while the other one attacks the pawns. Remember this rule when your opponent wants to outsmart you with some 1-c4 and 1-Nf3 as well. }
5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 c6 7. b3 Qe7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Qc1 Ne4 10. Ba3 Nd7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6
12. Qa3 c5
