[White "A Stonewall Concise Repertoire"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ To finish this theoretical part, let's have a look at the lines where White does not go g3 right away or not at all. I'll be honest about it : you won't only see pure Stonewall structures here, as they work better for Black with a White bishop on g2. }
2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 d5 5. Bd3 c6 6. Nge2 Bd6 7. f3
{ This is a dangerous plan that Black has to know about. The Stonewall is supposed to be stable in the centre, so remember the idea here. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Qe7 9. Qc2 Kh8
{ Getting away from the 'hot' a2-g8 diagonal and preparing to take on c4, followed by e5 advance. }
10. Bd2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nbd7 12. e4 e5 13. exf5 exd4 14. Nxd4 Qe5
{ With a double attack on the knight and the pawn on h2, which wins. } *


[White "A Stonewall Concise Repertoire"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ To finish this theoretical part, let's have a look at the lines where White does not go g3 right away or not at all. I'll be honest about it : you won't only see pure Stonewall structures here, as they work better for Black with a White bishop on g2. }
2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. Qc2 b6
{ In general, if we are allowed to fianchetto the bishop in the Dutch, we should aim to do so. }
5. e3 Bb7 6. f3 c5
{ We can't go d5 as White would trade and force us to recapture with a piece, but the Qc2 is not protecting the d-pawn anymore. }
7. d5 Bd6 8. Bd2 O-O 9. O-O-O Na6 10. a3 Nc7 11. e4 Be5
{ Intending to put the bishop on the d4 square and play on the queenside with a6-b5. }
*


[White "A Stonewall Concise Repertoire"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ To finish this theoretical part, let's have a look at the lines where White does not go g3 right away or not at all. I'll be honest about it : you won't only see pure Stonewall structures here, as they work better for Black with a White bishop on g2. }
2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. Nf3 Bb4
{ An idea 'borrowed' from the Nimzo-Indian, pinning the c3 knight and fighting for the e4 square. }
5. Qb3 Qe7 6. g3 b6 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O Bxc3 9. Qxc3 O-O
{ This is a standard Queen's Indian plan, that I also treated in my Killer Dutch Middlegames. Now Black goes d6-c5, put a knight on e4 and the other one on d7. White does have the bishop pair but he's only marginally better. Beware of White plans based on d5 and c5. }
*


[White "A Stonewall Concise Repertoire"]
[Black "2-Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3 Be6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Nge2 Qd7
{ Black goes h5, Bf7 and g6 if he needs to guard f5 or g5 is there's no pressure against it to take over on the kingside. Another line that White chooses much too often compared to its objective value in my opinion. }
*


[White "A Stonewall Concise Repertoire"]
[Black "2-Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 d5 4. e3 e6
{ then prepare to play first a6  (to prevent a check on b5)  , then c5. That's all. }
