2... fxg4 3. h3 d5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bf4 c5 6. e4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Bb5 dxe4 9.
Qc4 a6 10. Rd1 Qb6 11. Ba4 Bd7 12. hxg4 e5 13. Be3 Qxb2 14. Bb3 Qxc3+ 15. Qxc3
Bb4 { Black gets his queen back and is now two pawns up. } *


[White "The Author In Action !"]
[Black "kleopl vs. Le Ruyet, Leopold"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is from a memorable Titled Tuesday for me where I got to play Wojtasczek and Firouzja, and was actually a move away from beating the Iranian phenom, before scalping two GMs at the end of the tournament. This game was played right after my loss to Firouzja. }
1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 c6 5. d4 d5 6. Nh3 Be7 7. O-O Ne4 8. Qc2 h5
{ Charge ! Let me be clear : this is NOT a good idea objectively, but the Rapport lines have in general little to do with objectivity and everything to do with the man in front of you. Besides, one can succumb to indecency once or twice...or ten times. Can't he ? }
9. b3 h4 10. f3
{ Black is already for choice after this !   10.Nxe4  dxe4  11.Rd1  hxg3  12.hxg3  Nd7  and the computer changes its mind all the time. I suspect Black went too far too quickly but this is too general an assessment for such positions. }
10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 hxg3 12. hxg3 g5
{ No need to go bonkers here, as Black had a much more reliable option.   12...c5 !  where it transpires that White's development is actually not that impressive and we get to strike in the centre first ! }
13. e4 { To a wing attack, he blasts the centre open. Fair play. } 13... g4 14.
fxg4
{ 14.Nf4  gxf3  15.Bxf3  dxe4  16.Bh5+  was the move I had missed, after which Black is in big trouble. }
14... dxe4 15. Bb2 Bf6 16. Qe3 Na6 17. Rad1 Nb4 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Ba3
{ 19.a3  would have sufficed to secure White's consequent edge, as I can't go to d3 anymore. }
19... Nc2
{ A piece up, it's now curtains on the other side. Some would call it lucky but there is a risk/reward ratio in chess to justify my enterprising/downright nutso galore play ! }
20. Qd2 Nxa3 21. Nf4 c5 22. Nd5 Bxd4+ 23. Rf2 Be6 24. Qf4 Bxd5 25. cxd5 Qxd5
26. Kf1 O-O-O 27. Qxf5+ Qxf5 28. Rxf5 Nc2 *


[White "The Author In Action !"]
[Black "ondozimurtez vs. Le Ruyet, Leopold"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 d5 5. Nc3 c6 6. Nf3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. cxd5
exd5 9. b3
{ A curious mix-up. I fail to see how b3 is useful when Ba3 is impossible and there is no c4 pawn to defend. }
9... a5
{ Natural and perfectly playable, but I could also have gone Ne4 right away, followed by Nd7-f6, in which case a5 might reveal itself to be superfluous with the knight not going to a6. }
10. Bb2 Na6
{ 10...f4 !  If I did not play in such a stereotypical way, I would have found this natural move, after which not only do I foment queenside expansion but also a kingside offensive. The computer says equal but I'd take Black's easy plans any day ! }
11. e3 b6 12. Re1 Bb7 13. Rc1 Rc8
{ It's fascinating to me how Stockfish thinks this position is overwhelming for White when usually he has very little is this setup. So it appears that after all in this precise position it may have been smarter to go Ne4 to challenge the Nc3. Yes I know it's in the Theory Section of this book, and I should start using my own stuff someday ! }
14. Na4 c5
{ An instructive mistake !   14...Nb8  is what the computer likes but I would rather select   14...Ne4  Though once again White should be for choice. Still a human may not react so cleanly to a further c5 push. }
15. dxc5
{ 15.Ng5 !  Re8  16.dxc5  bxc5  17.Bxf6  wins the d5 pawn and the game. } 15...
bxc5 16. a3 { 16.Ng5 !  With the same idea. } 16... Ne4 17. Bf1 Nc7 18. Nd2 Ne6
{ Suddenly I like Black again, showing that it's not so easy to play White against this system ! }
19. Nxe4 { Please refer to the Take on e4 chapter ! } 19... fxe4 20. Bg2 Ng5
21. Nc3 Nf3+
{ A bit too optimistic as I could have prepared it first by protecting the d5 pawn. }
22. Bxf3 exf3 23. Nxd5 Qd7 24. Kh1 Qh3 25. Rg1 Rf5
{ But this is more critical, as we both missed White's defence that gives him the upper hand !   25...Rcd8 !  with a mess where Black should be the favourite, was best. }
26. Qf1
{ Now Black is just a piece up for nothing   26.Nf4 !  Bxf4  27.gxf4  Rh5  28.Rxg7+  Kf8  29.Qd6+  Ke8  30.Qe7  should have been the proper punishment. }
26... Qxf1 27. Rgxf1 Bxd5
{ The remainder only exists due this being a blitz game, but there's nothing left to see. }
28. Rfd1 Bf8 29. Rd3 Bf7 30. Kg1 a4 31. bxa4 c4 32. Rd4 Ra5 33. Rf4 Rxa4 34.
Rxf3 Bxa3 35. Bxa3 Rxa3 36. Rf4 c3 37. Rd4 c2 38. Rd2 Bg6 39. Kf1 Rb3 40. Ke2
Rb1 41. Rdxc2 Rxc1 42. Rxc1 Rxc1 43. g4 Rh1 44. Kf3 Rxh2 45. Kg3 Rh1 46. f4 Ra1
47. f5 Bxf5 48. gxf5 Kf7 49. Kf4 Kf6 50. e4 Rf1+ 51. Kg4 Ke5 52. Kg5 Kxe4 53.
f6 Rxf6 54. Kh5 Rg6 55. Kh4 Kf3 56. Kh5 Kf4 57. Kh4 Rh6# { Normal } *


[White "The Author In Action !"]
[Black "ChessExplained vs. Le Ruyet, Leopold"]
[Result "*"]

{ So here I had the opportunity to play IM Christof Sielecki, one of the most famous online instructors around and Chessable household. No doubt preparing for his 1-Nf3 repertoire, he had some nasty surprises up his sleeves ! }
1. Nf3 f5 2. g3 Nf6
{ 2...b6  3.Bg2  Bb7  4.O-O  Nf6  5.d4  and here e6 would bring about a position reminiscent of a QID while g6 offers a strange but playable version of the Leningrad Dutch. If the further options don't satisfy you I would advise going for those lines to get interesting middlegames.   5.d3  e6  6.e4  fxe4  7.Ng5  Nc6  8.dxe4  e5  is also not much for White, with the added bonus that Black can vary at every move after d3 and still be fine. }
3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 c6
{ I used to prefer this move order against any White Anglo-Reti tries but this game has cured me of any illusion that c6 is more than an overripen lemon. Instead Black needs to go for something else. Right now I would argue for   4...d5  5.O-O  Bd6  6.d3  O-O  7.Nc3   7.cxd5  in order to prevent the following idea is favored by the computer but I would feel fine playing this position after the critical Na6-c5-e6 maneuver.  7...exd5  8.Nc3  Na6  This reminds me of a Pirc with the e-pawn having gone e5xd6. Not the best possible line but it's hard for me to believe this is not at least decent for Black.  7...dxc4 !  White was ready to go e4 and we need to act in the centre before he does.  8.dxc4  Nc6  This is why c6 is such a poor choice. Now Black plays e5 and gets an objectively inferior but acceptable middlegame. }
5. O-O d5 6. d3 Bd6
{ 6...Be7  would have been preferable, as the bishop won't get hit by e4-e5, but when I see that at almost every move the computer wants to go c5 later on, it is the clear sign that something went wrong with Black's move order choice. }
7. Nc3 O-O
{ It now goes from bad to worse.   7...dxc4  8.dxc4  e5  9.c5  Bc7  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8  11.b4  is a rather pitous endgame, as White has already started his queenside operations while we developed horribly, and though the computer believes this is only slightly better for the first player, I wouldn't want to land in there, not to mention the fact that it betrays every notion of playing a Stonewall. }
8. e4 fxe4 9. dxe4 Be7
{ I should at least capture on e4, though my e6 pawn would then have a target on his back.   9...dxe4  10.Ng5  Be7  11.Ngxe4  Qxd1  12.Rxd1  e5  Now I'm reminded of bad Killer Dutch endgames with White having absolute control over the e4 square and Black being deprived of counterplay. }
10. exd5 exd5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Bg5
{ A tiny slip, apparently Bf4 was much more efficient. Still, White is at the very least much better. }
12... Nc6 13. Nd4
{ After my last move, my opponent went in the tank @@StartBracket@@if you can call it that in blitz@@EndBracket@@ for almost two minutes before playing this natural move. I suspect that it had all been theory for him up to then. }
13... Nxd4
{ Helping White out. I somehow thought I would keep d5 covered with a bishop on f7 and play Rc8-c4 but I'm simply never in time for that.   13...Bg4 !  14.Qa4  Qd7  And at least if White wants the d5 pawn he'll have to trade his dark-squared bishop, giving us two bishops in a completely open field to fish for compensations, however slim. }
14. Qxd4 Be6 15. Rfe1 Bf7 16. Rad1 Qa5
{ Deprived of good options, I go for counterplay and realize to my horror what I've just done. }
17. Rxe7
{ A short game that I hope illustrates how important it is to think your move order in advance against those Reti-English systems when you've decided to go Dutch. Always learn from your losses, however painful ! }
*


[White "The Author In Action !"]
[Black "Trompovsk2245 vs. Le Ruyet, Leopold"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. Nf3 d5 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 c6 7. b3 Qe7 8. a4 a5
9. Ba3 b6
{ Sometimes I like to test new waters and here, even though I of course knew that taking on a3 was best, I was curious as to how my opponent would punish this try. Please refer to the Theory Section. }
10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. e3 Na6 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Nd2
{ 13.Nc3  is what White is supposed to do here, but whether he is better at all is another question, as Black still can go for the usual Nb4 and c5 plan. }
13... O-O 14. Rc1 c5 15. Qc2 Rac8 16. Qb1 Nb4 17. Rfd1 Ne4 18. f3
{ Now comes the fun part ! } 18... Nxd2 19. Rxd2 cxd4 20. exd4 f4
{ White's bishop won't play on the long diagonal and dc4 may get our own bishop roaring at any point. }
21. Re1 Ba6
{ Ahem. Roaring on the long diagonal I said. In my defence I can still come back on the next move I suppose. }
22. Bf1 dxc4
{ Or not. It's a blitz game but still, my moves have no logic attached to them. }
23. Nxc4
{ 23.bxc4 !  Of course White needs to keep control over the d5 square ! } 23...
Qc6 { 23...Bxc4 !  24.Bxc4   24.bxc4  fxg3  24...Nd5  with equal chances. } 24.
Ne5
{ 24.Qe4  When under attack, trade queens ! Still Black is only marginally worse after any reasonable move, including trading queens. }
24... Qb7 { 24...Qc3 ! } 25. Bc4 Bxc4 26. bxc4 fxg3 27. hxg3 Rxf3
{ Objectively wrong and justified only by my opponent's lack of time. I should have gone   27...Nc6  and beg for a draw. But then I would not have won, would I ?! }
28. Nxf3 Qxf3 29. Rg2 Rxc4 30. Rxe6 Rxd4 31. Re8+ Kf7 32. Rf2 Qxf2+ 33. Kxf2
Kxe8 34. Qxh7 Kf8
{ A fascinating endgame has arisen. Suffice it to say it should be a fortress but somehow, with seconds ticking I ended up on top. }
